:: FlightPrep [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Preflight — reviewing materials"])>>

<div class="scenario-title">The Wall</div>
<div class="scenario-subtitle">A mountain weather scenario — KBJC to KASE</div>

It's a Saturday morning in late July. You and Rachel are flying from Rocky Mountain Metropolitan Airport in Broomfield to Aspen for your friend Ben's wedding. The rehearsal dinner is tonight at 7 PM — Ben asked you specifically to be there early to help set up. Rachel's already dressed for dinner and her garment bag is in the back of the Skylane.

The 182T is fueled, preflighted, and parked on the Sheltair ramp. The sun is already warm at 8:30 AM, and you can see the front range to the west. A few cumulus are starting to pop over the peaks, but that's normal for a summer morning. You've got time to review your materials before starting the engine.

<strong>Review your preflight materials:</strong>

<div class="chart-disclaimer">Charts, weather data, and performance calculations in this scenario are from the period in which it was written and may no longer be current. Use the materials provided here — not current publications — as the scenario is designed around them.</div>

<<link '<span class="preflight-btn">Weather Briefing</span>' "Preflight-Weather">><<set $readWeather to true>><</link>>
<<link '<span class="preflight-btn">Flight Plan & Route</span>' "Preflight-FlightPlan">><<set $readFlightPlan to true>><</link>>
<<link '<span class="preflight-btn">Density Altitude Worksheet</span>' "Preflight-DensityAlt">><<set $readDensityAlt to true>><</link>>
<<link '<span class="preflight-btn">Area Map</span>' "Preflight-Map">><<set $readMap to true>><</link>>

<<if $readWeather and $readFlightPlan and $readDensityAlt and $readMap>>
<hr>
You've reviewed all your materials. Time to decide.

<<link '<span class="preflight-btn">☑ Begin Flight</span>' "Opening">><</link>>
<<elseif $readWeather or $readFlightPlan or $readDensityAlt or $readMap>>
<hr>
<em>You haven't reviewed all the materials yet. In the real world, you'd want to look at everything before departure. Take your time.</em>

<<link '<span class="preflight-btn">Begin Flight Anyway</span>' "Opening">><</link>>
<</if>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: Preflight-Weather [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reviewed weather briefing"])>>
<strong>Standard Briefing — Denver AFSS</strong>
<em>Briefer: "Good morning, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot. Standard briefing, Broomfield to Aspen, Cessna 182. Here's what I've got for you."</em>

<strong>Synopsis:</strong>
A broad upper-level ridge is weakening over the central Rockies. A Pacific shortwave trough is approaching from the west, expected to arrive late this afternoon. This pattern is typical for summertime mountain thunderstorm development, with earlier-than-normal convective initiation possible — by late morning over the highest terrain.

<strong>Current conditions:</strong>
<div class="metar-block">KBJC 111353Z 18006KT 10SM FEW080 25/08 A3012 RMK AO2
KASE 111353Z 17010KT 10SM FEW040 BKN065 08/01 A3014
KEGE 111356Z 00000KT 10SM FEW110 05/M02 A3010
KRIL 111353Z AUTO 01004KT 10SM OVC100 12/M01 A2999
KLXV 111353Z AUTO 12004KT 10SM OVC060 01/M03 A3024</div>

<strong>Terminal Forecast — KASE:</strong>
<div class="metar-block">TAF KASE 111416Z 1114/1212
  1114/1118 17010G20KT P6SM VCSH SCT040 OVC060
  FM111800 19011G20KT P6SM VCSH SCT070 BKN100
  FM111830 22014G24KT P6SM VCSH SCT060 BKN100
  PROB30 1120/1202 VRB22G33KT -TSRA BKN060CB BKN070
  FM120200 19007KT P6SM VCSH FEW060 BKN110</div>

<strong>Briefer notes:</strong>
<em>"Here's the thing — those cumulus are building earlier than the models predicted yesterday. Leadville is already showing overcast at six thousand AGL, and the ASOS at Aspen has scattered at four thousand with a broken deck at six-five. The TAF for Aspen holds reasonable VFR through 18Z, but there's a PROB30 for thunderstorms by 20Z. I'd say your window is the next three to four hours. After that, the mountains are going to be doing their thing. PIREPs are thin this morning — one Bonanza reported moderate turbulence over Red Table VOR at 14,000 about forty minutes ago. No current AIRMETs for your route, but I'd expect Sierra and Tango to come out later this morning."</em>

<strong>Winds aloft (relevant levels):</strong>
<div class="metar-block">FT     12000    15000    18000
DEN    2515+07  2625+01  2735-10
GJT    2420+05  2530-01  2640-12</div>

<strong>NOTAMs:</strong>
Nothing significant for KBJC, KASE, or the route. KLXV: PAPI RWY 16 out of service.

[[← Back to Flight Prep|FlightPrep]]

:: Preflight-FlightPlan [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reviewed flight plan"])>>
<strong>VFR Flight Plan — N472GF</strong>

<div class="flight-plan">
<strong>Aircraft:</strong> Cessna 182T Skylane (G1000)
<strong>N-number:</strong> N472GF
<strong>TAS:</strong> 130 KTAS at 12,500
<strong>Departure:</strong> KBJC (Rocky Mountain Metro) — Elev 5,673 ft
<strong>Destination:</strong> KASE (Aspen-Pitkin County) — Elev 7,837 ft
<strong>Route:</strong> KBJC direct REDSM V8 DBL direct KASE
<strong>Altitude:</strong> 14,500 ft MSL (westbound — odd + 500 VFR)
<strong>Distance:</strong> 115 nm
<strong>ETE:</strong> 0+53 (plus 15 min climb)
<strong>Fuel on board:</strong> 65 gallons (5.2 hrs endurance at 12.5 GPH cruise)
<strong>Fuel required:</strong> ~18 gal (1.1 hr flight + 45 min reserve = 1.85 hrs)
<strong>Passengers:</strong> 1 (Rachel)
<strong>Remarks:</strong> VFR flight following requested with Denver Center

<strong>Alternates considered:</strong>
KEGE (Eagle County) — 38 nm NW of Aspen, 6,547 ft, 9,000 ft runway
KRIL (Rifle) — 44 nm NW of Aspen, 5,537 ft, 7,000 ft runway, ILS
KAEJ (Buena Vista) — 43 nm S of Leadville, 7,950 ft, 8,303 ft runway
KLXV (Leadville) — 26 nm E of Aspen, 9,934 ft, 6,400 ft runway

<strong>Minimum terrain crossing altitude:</strong> 14,500 ft MSL over the Continental Divide via V-8 (MEA 14,500). Terrain along route ranges from 8,000 ft in the valleys to 14,000+ ft along the Divide.
</div>

<strong>Notes on the route:</strong> The V-8 airway crosses the Continental Divide near Red Table VOR (DBL) at a published MEA of 14,500 ft. The Cessna 182T service ceiling is 18,100 ft (normally aspirated). At density altitudes above 12,000 ft, expect significantly reduced climb performance — plan your crossing altitude before reaching the mountains, not over them. Terrain clearance in the valleys between the Divide and Aspen is critical. The Roaring Fork Valley runs northwest-southeast and provides a natural corridor into KASE, but it narrows significantly south of Glenwood Springs.

[[← Back to Flight Prep|FlightPrep]]

:: Preflight-DensityAlt [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reviewed density altitude worksheet"])>>
<strong>Density Altitude Worksheet — Late July</strong>

<div class="density-alt-worksheet">
<strong>KBJC (departure):</strong>
  Field elevation: 5,673 ft
  Temperature: 25°C (77°F) at 0845L
  Altimeter: 30.12
  <strong>Density altitude: 8,100 ft</strong>

<strong>KASE (destination):</strong>
  Field elevation: 7,837 ft
  Forecast temp at arrival (~1030L): 18°C (64°F)
  Altimeter: 30.14
  <strong>Density altitude: 10,200 ft</strong>

<strong>KLXV (alternate — if needed):</strong>
  Field elevation: 9,934 ft
  Temperature: 1°C (34°F) at 0845L
  Altimeter: 30.24
  <strong>Density altitude: 9,800 ft</strong>
  NOTE: By noon, if temp reaches 15°C → <strong>density altitude: 12,400 ft</strong>

<strong>Performance reference — C182T at density altitude:</strong>

<table class="airport-table">
<tr><th>DA (ft)</th><th>Takeoff Roll</th><th>Rate of Climb</th><th>Landing Roll</th></tr>
<tr><td>Sea level</td><td>795 ft</td><td>924 fpm</td><td>590 ft</td></tr>
<tr><td>5,000</td><td>1,015 ft</td><td>700 fpm</td><td>640 ft</td></tr>
<tr><td>8,000</td><td>1,355 ft</td><td>480 fpm</td><td>710 ft</td></tr>
<tr><td>10,000</td><td>1,650 ft</td><td>340 fpm</td><td>770 ft</td></tr>
<tr><td>12,000</td><td>2,100 ft</td><td>195 fpm</td><td>840 ft</td></tr>
</table>

<strong>Key considerations:</strong>
At density altitudes above 10,000 ft, expect takeoff rolls nearly double the sea-level distance. Climb rates drop dramatically — at DA 12,000, you're getting less than 200 fpm. If you need to land at a high-altitude airport in the afternoon when temperatures peak, recalculate before committing. Aspen's runway is 8,006 ft, which provides adequate margin at DA 10,000. Leadville's runway is 6,400 ft — manageable in the morning, but if DA climbs above 12,000, the math gets tight, especially at maximum gross weight.

The C182T's service ceiling of 18,100 ft is a theoretical number at maximum gross. Your practical ceiling today — the altitude where you can sustain 100 fpm climb — is closer to 15,500 ft with two passengers and full fuel. That still clears the Divide, but there's less margin than the POH suggests.
</div>

[[← Back to Flight Prep|FlightPrep]]

