<strong>Area Map — Route overview:</strong>

<div class="sectional-container">
<script id="area-map-zoom-data" type="text/plain">%%AREA_MAP_DATA_URI%%</script>
<img src="%%AREA_MAP_DATA_URI%%" onclick="openZoomChart('area-map-zoom-data')" style="cursor:zoom-in; max-width:100%; border:1px solid #999; border-radius:4px;" alt="Annotated area map — KBJC to KASE with terrain and airports">
<div class="sectional-label">Annotated route overview — key airports, terrain, and the Continental Divide<br><em>Click to open in zoomable viewer</em></div>
</div>

<div class="chart-disclaimer"><em>This chart is provided for training and educational purposes only. It is not intended for navigation and may not reflect current aeronautical information. Always use current, officially published FAA charts and publications for flight planning and navigation.</em></div>

<strong>Terrain notes:</strong> This route crosses the Continental Divide. Terrain rises from 5,600 ft at KBJC to over 14,000 ft along the Divide west of Red Table VOR (DBL). The highest terrain along the direct route is in the Sawatch Range and Elk Mountains, where peaks exceed 14,000 ft (Mount Elbert 14,440, Mount Massive 14,428, Capitol Peak 14,131). Valleys between the ranges drop to 7,500–9,000 ft but narrow significantly. The Roaring Fork Valley provides the primary corridor into Aspen from the north/northwest. Mountain passes — Hagerman (11,925 ft), Independence (12,095 ft), and Fremont (11,318 ft) — can be useful visual references but are not reliable escape routes when weather closes in.

<strong>Key terrain trap warning:</strong> The valleys south and east of Aspen form a box canyon environment. If you descend into a valley and weather closes behind you, your options are extremely limited. Never descend into a valley you aren't certain you can fly out of.

[[← Back to Flight Prep|FlightPrep]]

:: Opening [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Departed KBJC, climbing westbound over foothills"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" loop volume 0.3 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "atc-ambience" loop volume 0.08 play>><</if>>

Twenty-five minutes west of Broomfield. You're at fourteen thousand five hundred feet, coring up through the foothills toward the Continental Divide. The 182 is burning 11 gallons per hour, right on the numbers. Rachel, your passenger, has stopped being impressed by the view and is studying the cloud formations ahead with the intensity of someone who knows her life depends on what you decide next.

The weather picture in front of you is exactly the kind that kills pilots because it's not obviously lethal. Not yet.

To the southwest, along the Sawatch Range ridgeline, build-ups are developing. Concentrated. The kind of cumulus that's growing at maybe five hundred feet per minute—some have bases around thirteen thousand, some are reaching toward seventeen. Could go either way. Could stay scattered. Could organize into something worse.

Directly on your course toward Red Table VOR: growing cumulus. Not towering yet. Not vertically developed. But visible, persistent, and definitely bigger than they were ten minutes ago. There's a gap—visible now, but how wide? Two miles? Three? Hard to judge distance in this light.

To the north, toward the Gore Range, the weather looks cleaner. Scattered clouds, good visibility, what looks like decent wind shear that's tearing up any organization. That direction would mean a deviation, sure. But doable.

Behind you, the Front Range and the prairie are crystal clear. KBJC is still good. But the forecast said afternoon build-ups along the Front Range, and you've got maybe four hours of good weather before that window closes.

You've been calling Denver Center every ten minutes. Last report: "Several aircraft deviating in the Red Table area—no specific recommendation, advise your intentions." Translation: we don't know what to tell you.

The Beech Baron three thousand feet ahead reported moderate turbulence at Red Table at fifteen thousand forty minutes ago. But here's the thing—the Baron *continued* to Aspen and landed safely. That fact sits in your head like a stone. If the Baron made it...

You called Aspen on Unicom and got the ATIS: "KASE reporting scattered at nine thousand AGL, winds two-one-zero at twelve, VFR. Temperature two-three, dew point two-one." Aspen is fine. The approach is fine. You're eighty-five miles away.

But you also picked up Rifle on the radio while you were dialing around. "KRIE reporting winds two-seven-zero at two-two, gusting three-eight." Ninety-degree crosswind gusting thirty-eight knots. That's above most pilots' comfort. Even yours. Maybe especially yours, because you respect the wind enough to know what you don't want to fight.

Temperature is three degrees warmer than forecast. You knew that meant instability. More moisture. More lift. More potential for organization.

Fuel: fifty-seven gallons remaining. Four hours-plus endurance. Eighty-five miles to go.

Rachel shifts in the seat. "Those clouds on the left are getting bigger."

She's right. They are.

You click to Denver Center. "Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, requesting updated weather and traffic picture around Red Table, and current conditions Aspen."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, Aspen still reporting scattered at nine, light winds. Red Table area continues to see scattered building cumulus, upper-level winds now showing some shear. No specific convective returns on radar yet, but watch for development. Traffic continues through the area. How do you want to proceed?"

The controller is asking the question you have to answer.

You have four doors in front of you right now. Pick one.

<<link "A. Continue direct toward Red Table. The Baron made it through. Aspen is VFR. The cumulus might not develop further. You've got this." "A-ContinueDirect">>
	<<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continued direct toward Red Table"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Deviate north toward the Eagle County corridor. The weather looks lighter that direction and you'd rather dodge now than dance around cells." "B-DeviateNorth">>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Requested deviation north toward Eagle County"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Contact Denver Flight Service on 122.2 for an updated weather picture before committing to the crossing. Information is your friend right now." "C-ContactFSS">>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Called Flight Service for updated weather briefing"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "D. Climb to sixteen thousand five hundred. Better terrain clearance, better visibility over developing weather. The 182 can do it at this weight." "D-ClimbHigher">>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Climbed to 16,500 for altitude and visibility"])>>
<</link>>

:: A-ContinueDirect [scenario branch-a]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "atc-ambience" loop volume 0.2 play>><</if>>

Ten miles from Red Table.

The word is *fast*. Cumulus gone from developing to towering. Like someone switched the weather display to a new scene. The bases are around thirteen thousand, maybe thirteen-five. The tops are visibly climbing. Two thousand feet a minute, maybe more. The rain shaft on the north side of the closest cell is visible from here—gray column, dense, organized.

Moderate turbulence hits. Not warning turbulence. The real thing. The 182 shudders and drops maybe a hundred feet in the space of a heartbeat. Your stomach comes up with it.

Rain on the windshield. Not occasional drops. Continuous. Streaking.

The gap you were watching—the one that was maybe eight miles wide on the left side of your course—is visible but *shrinking*. Cells are merging. Moving together. The sunlit terrain on the other side that you could see five minutes ago is still visible but through increasingly gray filter.

Rachel grabs the armrest with both hands. "Mike, those clouds are getting really big."

Her voice is calm but her knuckles are white.

The radio explodes. "Denver Center, Citation Four-Four-Seven-Hotel just experienced severe turbulence and hail encounter Red Table vicinity, currently fifteen thousand, unable to maintain altitude, requesting immediate vectors."

Denver Center: "Citation Four-Four-Seven-Hotel, copy severe turbulence and hail Red Table. Turn right heading three-five-zero immediately, proceed to Eagle County. Multiple aircraft reporting significant activity Red Table area."

You're still ten miles away.

The cells ahead—the ones you were going to thread between—are now visibly a wall. Gap is four miles and closing.

ATC: "Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, be advised, traffic reports severe turbulence at Red Table vicinity. We're recommending deviation for inbound traffic. How do you want to proceed?"

Rachel looks at you. You can hear her breathing over the engine noise.

Three doors now. Two of them require immediate action.

<<link "A1. Execute immediate one-eighty back east. You can see the weather deteriorating faster than forecast. Turn around now, get east of the mountains while the Front Range is still okay." "A1-TurnBack180">>
	<<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Turned back 180 degrees, heading east"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "A2. Bank hard left toward the Eagle River valley. Deviation under pressure, but workable. The valley floor is at six thousand, the weather is lighter that direction." "A2-DeviateEagle">>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Deviated north to Eagle River valley"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "A3. Push the narrowing gap. You can see sunlit terrain on the other side. The cells aren't quite merged. You can fit through. The 182 can handle it." "A3-PushGap">>
	<<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 2>>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Pressed toward narrowing gap between cells"])>>
<</link>>

:: A1-TurnBack180 [scenario branch-a]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" loop volume 0.3 play>><</if>>

You call it immediately.

"Denver Center, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, turning one-eighty heading back toward the Front Range. We'll sort out the weather situation that direction."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger, turning one-eighty approved, frequency change to Colorado Springs approved when you're ready."

You bank the 182 hard left. The turbulence smooths almost immediately heading east. The wall of cells falls behind you. Relief floods through you like a physical thing. Rachel exhales—you didn't realize she was holding her breath.

"Good call," she says quietly.

But good calls at fourteen thousand feet in Colorado don't come cheap, and the debt always comes due.

Fifteen minutes later, approaching the Front Range foothills, Denver Center relays new information. The tone of the controller's voice has changed. It's got that edge—the one that means the weather picture just got worse, not better.

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, be advised, convective SIGMET now issued from Castle Rock northbound to Boulder. Multiple thunderstorm cells developing along the Front Range. VFR traffic is requested to use caution."

Through the windshield ahead: new build-ups. Not in the mountains—along the foothills. Between you and KBJC. Scattered, with visible gaps between them, but they're growing. You can see the anvil being sheared off one cell to the north. Organized. Developing.

And behind you, the wall over the Divide is now solid. No gaps. No way back.

You're between two weather systems. Rachel's watching this unfold with the same expression she had at Red Table—calm on the surface, running calculations underneath.

Fuel: fifty gallons. Altitude: fourteen thousand five hundred. You're committed to landing east of the mountains now. The question is where.

Denver Center: "Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, current observations: KBJC winds three-one-zero at one-eight gusting two-eight, visibility two miles in rain, lightning within five miles northwest. KAPA Centennial, winds two-seven-zero at one-two, scattered three thousand AGL, VFR. Traffic is landing both airports."

Rachel turns toward you. "Are those thunderstorms between us and the airport?"

"Yeah. But there are gaps. And Centennial is clear south."

She nods. She's not panicking. She's waiting to see which option you pick.

Two doors now.

<<link "A1a. Continue toward KBJC. The scattered cells over the metro are manageable with looking. You've threaded between weather before. It's your home airport. You know it. Get Rachel there." "A1a-LandKBJC">>
	<<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Pressed toward KBJC through developing Front Range storms"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "A1b. Divert to Centennial south of the metro. Weather is clearer to the south. It's only thirty miles further. You'll take the rental and drive—it's safer than threading through cells with lightning nearby." "A1b-DivertKAPA">>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverted to Centennial Airport south of Denver"])>>
<</link>>

:: A1a-LandKBJC [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "atc-ambience" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "rain-windshield" loop volume 0.25 play>><</if>>

You press toward KBJC.

Broomfield Approach clears you down to five thousand. The scattered cells over the metro are manageable—not ideal, but manageable. You maintain visual with the ground, thread between two cell complexes with moderate turbulence and steady rain, and keep your heading toward home.

"Broomfield Tower, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, five thousand, requesting direct to thirty-right."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrol, cleared direct thirty-right, descend to three thousand, altimeter three-zero-one-two."

Three thousand. Terrain is dropping. You're below the weather now.

Final approach for thirty-right. The wind is 310 at 18 gusting 28—a stiff crosswind, ninety degrees to the runway. The 182's demonstrated crosswind component is around 15 knots. This gust component is more than double that. But you've handled gusty crosswinds before. The runway is eight thousand feet long. You've got plenty of runway.

You set up the crab. Twenty degrees into the wind. The landing gear is down, flaps are twenty. RPM in the green. Airspeed one thousand feet out is seventy knots, perfect.

At 50 feet, a gust rolls the 182 ten degrees right. Your hands are steady—aileron correction, nudge the nose left with rudder. The airplane settles back.

At the threshold, you transition to the slip. Right wing low, left rudder applied, kick the right main gear down first. Touch. Left main follows. Nosewheel touches smooth.

On rollout, a gust shoves you left toward the grass. Immediate right rudder, a touch of brake. You hold the centerline. The landing is firm but on the stripe.

Safe.

Your pulse is 140. Sweat on your upper lip.

You taxi to the ramp and Rachel is very quiet. At the tiedown, after you've cut the engine and the props are still, she says:

"That last twenty minutes was not fun."

You don't answer. There's nothing to say.

You get a taxi to Ben's place. It's a four-hour drive to Aspen. You make the rehearsal dinner, barely. Ben says "rough flight?" and you say "interesting flight," and that's where the story ends for everyone except you and Rachel.


<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: The Home-Field Trap</strong>

You made two significant errors in this sequence. The first was continuing direct toward Red Table when the weather was deteriorating and alternatives existed. That one nearly cost you at the Divide.

But the recovery error—the one that matters for this ending—was choosing KBJC over Centennial when threading back through developing Front Range thunderstorms. The Baron had made it through the Divide because turning back was the right decision. But once you'd turned back and found weather between you and home, the correct decision was a second adaptive move: get down somewhere safe and close that became available.

Centennial was VFR, clear winds, and thirty miles further south. It required nothing more than a rental car and a 4.5-hour drive. KBJC required threading through cells with active lightning nearby. You chose the airport, not the safety.

This is a documented human factors trap called the "home field preference." Pilots disproportionately fixate on their home airport when returning from a bad situation, even when alternatives are demonstrably safer. Why? Because it's the known quantity. The familiar place. The one you've landed at a thousand times. Your brain wants to go there.

But your brain is also the thing that's killing pilots with 500-1000 hours in situations exactly like this.

The crosswind landing at KBJC was in your capability—you've got the hours and the skill. But it was also unnecessary. The weather at Centennial was better. The wind was lighter. The approach was uneventful. And you would have arrived only thirty minutes later at the rehearsal dinner.

Key lesson: Your departure airport is not always your best return airport. When the weather situation changes midway through your flight, re-evaluate your alternates with the same rigor you used at the preflight briefing. The nearest safe airport might not be the one you know best. Accept a slightly longer drive in a rental car. That's what they're for.

Hazardous attitudes: Get-there-itis influenced the initial continuation (the wedding in Aspen was important). But the real hazard was familiarity bias—the assumption that KBJC was the best option because it was home. The normalization of risk also played a role: "Traffic is still landing, it must be fine." Other pilots' acceptance of risk is not authorization for you to accept it.

Key takeaway: When you turn back and find weather between you and home, the mission is no longer "land at KBJC." The mission is "land somewhere safe." Those are not always the same thing. Flexibility in your destination is flexibility in your survival options. Use it.
</div>

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
	_step
<</for>>

<<link "Return to Start" "Opening">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: A1b-DivertKAPA [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" loop volume 0.3 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "atc-ambience" loop volume 0.08 play>><</if>>

You make the call.

"Denver, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, we're going to divert to Centennial. Better weather picture to the south."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger, Centennial is right traffic left base for seventeen-right, winds two-seven-zero at one-two, altimeter three-zero-one-three. Frequency change approved."

You contact Centennial Tower and the approach is immediate and clear. The weather down here is obviously better—the Front Range cells are concentrated over the Boulder-Broomfield corridor, piling up against the foothills. To the south, the metro is under broken clouds with good visibility beneath. You can see I-25 from altitude.

"Centennial Tower, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, left base for seventeen-right."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrol, clear to land seventeen-right. Winds one-seven-zero at ten, gusts one-five."

You hand-fly the approach. The 182 settles onto the runway smooth and easy. Landing at Centennial at 10:30 AM. One thousand six hundred feet of altitude gained, going south instead of west. It feels like a small thing but it was exactly the right decision.

Rachel looks around the unfamiliar FBO as you taxi in.

"Where are we?"

"Centennial. About thirty miles south of where we started."

"So we went backward."

"We went somewhere safe."

She considers this. Nods. Doesn't argue. 

The Signature FBO gets you a rental car in forty minutes. You load your flight bag into the trunk and point the car toward I-25 north, then I-70 west. Same drive from here as from KBJC—four hours maybe four and a half with traffic. You text Ben: *Weather got interesting. Landing south of Denver. Will see you for dinner.*

You arrive in Aspen at 3:15 PM. Not in time for the rehearsal setup. In time for the dinner. Ben sees you at the restaurant, looks at you both, and says, "Rough flight?"

"Interesting flight," you say.

"You okay?"

"We're fine. Made the right calls when we had to."

Rachel, over a drink later, says it this way: "I felt like we were working together, you and me. Like you were thinking the whole time, not just reacting."

That's the best compliment you could get.


<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: Adaptive Decision-Making Under Pressure</strong>

You made one significant error and then executed a sound recovery chain. The error was the initial decision to continue direct toward Red Table when the weather was deteriorating and alternatives existed. That nearly got you into a severe situation at the Divide.

But here's what matters: when you were caught in deteriorating conditions, you made the right call. The 180 back was correct. And then, when you found weather between you and home, you made the second critical decision: you recognized that KBJC was not your only option, and you picked the objectively safer one.

This is the mark of an adaptive pilot. You were flying the situation, not the airport. The mission was "get safely on the ground," not "get back to where you started." Centennial was VFR, had light winds, and required no threading through developing cells. The tradeoff was thirty miles of driving, which is nothing. 

The key insight: you evaluated your alternates twice. Once at the briefing (which you should have done but probably didn't focus on hard enough—Centennial would have been in your weather alternates if you'd done the proper alternate planning). And again in real-time when the situation changed. You updated your plan based on new information. That's exactly what the situation demanded.

The crosswind landing at KBJC would have been survivable—you've got the skill. But survivable is not the same as necessary. Safe is always better than necessary-but-survivable.

Hazardous attitudes: Get-there-itis influenced the initial continuation (Aspen, the wedding, the pressure to arrive). But you overcame it. Once you admitted that the original plan wasn't going to work, you pivoted.

Key lesson: The best pilots are not the ones who never hit obstacles. They're the ones who recognize obstacles early and change plans before the obstacle becomes a crisis. You recognized the weather at Red Table was developing faster than forecast. You turned back instead of pressing through. Then you recognized the Front Range alternative was better than threading through cells. Two decisions, both made with incomplete information, both correct.

Key takeaway: Mountain flying in Colorado requires flexibility. You need at least two good alternates to any crossing of the Continental Divide, and you need to be willing to use them. The rehearsal dinner was important, but it was never worth dying for. The fact that you made it on time anyway is the happy outcome. The real victory is that you would have made it safely even if you had to drive from Centennial. The schedule is always secondary to the safety margin. This is the difference between a professional pilot and a lucky one.
</div>

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
	_step
<</for>>

<<link "Return to Start" "Opening">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>

