:: A2-DeviateEagle [scenario branch-a]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" loop volume 0.3 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "atc-ambience" loop volume 0.1 play>><</if>>

You bank hard left. The 182's nose swings north.

"Denver Center, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, deviating north toward Eagle County VOR. Request direct Eagle County and advise any traffic in that flow."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, deviation approved. Proceed direct Eagle County. Be advised, Eagle VOR area showing scattered build-ups, Eagle County ATIS showing winds two-seven-zero at one-nine gusting two-eight. Additional traffic in the area—remain vigilant."

You're off the direct course now, burning time and distance to go around the deterioration at Red Table. The turbulence smooths as you move away from the organized cells developing along the ridgeline. The Gore Range to the north has scattered build-ups but nothing like the wall developing over the Sawatch. Thirty minutes of tense but manageable flying and you're overhead Eagle County VOR at fourteen thousand five hundred feet.

Below you: the wide valley of the Eagle River, I-70 snaking through it, the town of Eagle. Mountains rising on either side but the valley itself is open, accessible, with the airport sitting right there at the valley floor like an offered hand.

But between you and Aspen—between here and the Roaring Fork Valley on the other side of the ridge—solid weather. A line of moderate to heavy returns from Vail Pass southwest. Cells with bases around twelve thousand, tops well above you. The gap you might have threaded an hour ago has closed completely.

You call Denver Center for a real-time update.

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, be advised, now have solid line of moderate to heavy convective returns from Vail Pass area, southwest toward Independence Pass. Multiple aircraft diverting. Aspen weather updated: scattered thunderstorms developing to the north of the field, now visibility two miles rain, winds two-two-zero at fourteen gusting twenty-four."

Aspen is no longer sitting there as a clear option on the other side of this weather. The weather is now on top of Aspen.

Fuel remaining: forty-six gallons. The 182 cruises fifty nautical miles on a gallon at this altitude. Eagle is directly below. Rifle—where that monstrous crosswind gust is waiting—is thirty-eight miles to the west, still in the Eagle River valley, lower terrain.

Rachel's been watching this unfold.

"We're not going to make it through that, are we?"

"No. Not now."

"So what's the plan?"

You have three options, and they've narrowed considerably from where you started.

<<link "A2a. Land at Eagle County right now. Solid, long runway, good terrain, and they've got ground transport to Aspen. Take the shuttle. Safe and professional." "A2a-LandEagle">>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed at Eagle County Airport"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "A2b. Continue west to Rifle. Lower elevation, and the Roaring Fork Valley approach from the northwest might be passable even with the weather along the main ridge. It's workable if you're willing to descend through the weather." "A2b-TryRifle">>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continued west toward Rifle"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "A2c. Hold over Eagle for thirty minutes. Summer mountain storms move fast. Maybe a gap opens. Maybe the cells move east. Give the weather room to work and re-evaluate." "A2c-HoldEagle">>
	<<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Held over Eagle County waiting for weather to improve"])>>
<</link>>

:: A2a-LandEagle [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" loop volume 0.3 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "atc-ambience" loop volume 0.1 play>><</if>>

You make the call immediately.

"Denver, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot requesting descent into Eagle County. We're landing."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, squawk VFR, frequency change to Eagle County approved on 118.2. Have a good day."

You spiral down into the Eagle River valley. The 182 descends smoothly through scattered clouds. Terrain is rising on both sides but the valley is wide and the descent is clean.

Eagle County tower clears you to land on runway 24.

"Winds two-seven-zero at nineteen gusting twenty-eight, right traffic for twenty-four."

You hand-fly the approach. The wind is crosswind but reasonable compared to what Rifle was offering. You set up the crab, the PAPI shows you're good on glide path. Over the threshold, transition to a sideslip—right wing down, left rudder. The right main touches first. Left main follows. The landing is solid and on centerline. A gust on rollout gives you a push and you correct with right rudder and a dab of brake. 

The 182 settles. Safe.

Tower: "Excellent landing, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot. Taxi to Signature FBO, welcome to Eagle County."

It's 10:45 AM. You park at the FBO and grab your flight bag. Rachel stretches in the ramp and looks at the solid weather still piling up over the ridge to the south.

"So now what?"

"Shuttle to Aspen. Leaves at eleven-thirty."

"And the airplane?"

"Stays here until this system moves through. We fly home tomorrow."

She looks at the anvil tops rising above the ridge. They're still building.

"That was a lot of flying to end up on a bus."

"Better than the alternative."

She nods. Doesn't argue. You grab your bags from the airplane and head to the FBO lounge.

The shuttle departs at 11:30 AM sharp. You arrive in Aspen by 1:00 PM. Plenty of time for the rehearsal dinner. Plenty of time to breathe.

Ben is setting up centerpieces when you arrive. He looks relieved to see you.

"Hey, you made it. How was the flight?"

"Interesting," you say. It's becoming your standard answer.

"Everything okay?"

"Everything's fine. Weather made us adapt a bit."

He nods. That's all the debriefing he needs.


<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: Sound Adaptation and Knowing Your Limits</strong>

You made one initial error—continuing direct toward Red Table when the weather was deteriorating—but you executed the recovery perfectly. When you recognized that the original route was blocked by solid convection, you deviated north. When you arrived overhead Eagle and saw that Aspen was no longer accessible (scattered thunderstorms developing, visibility down to two miles), you made the keystone decision: you landed immediately at the nearest safe airport.

This is the mark of a professional decision-making process. You had the information—solid convective line, Aspen deteriorating, alternatives available. You evaluated your options (Eagle safe and accessible; Rifle had a marginal crosswind; holding was hoping instead of planning) and picked the objective best one.

The fact that you ended up on a bus instead of in the airplane is not a failure. It's a success. The mission was "get to Aspen safely for the rehearsal dinner." You accomplished that. The fact that you had to use ground transport for the last 40 miles is irrelevant. The airplane got you 85 miles west of your departure point and then waited for better weather. That's exactly what it's supposed to do.

Key insight: Many pilots—a large portion, actually—wouldn't have landed at Eagle. They would have tried Rifle. Not because Rifle was obviously safer (it wasn't—the crosswind was 36 knots gusting, well above the 182's demonstrated limit). But because Rifle was closer to Aspen. Because it kept the airplane in the story a bit longer. Because of get-there-itis.

But you got there. You just got there by bus instead of by air.

The other critical decision was the one you made when you diviated north at Red Table. Instead of pressing through deteriorating weather toward your original destination, you recognized the threat and moved to a new plan. This required admitting that the original plan wasn't going to work—that's hard for pilots. We're trained to land the airplane, no matter what. But landing it in the middle of a developing thunderstorm while trying to get somewhere is not landing it well.

Hazardous attitudes: Get-there-itis was the original driver (the wedding in Aspen, the pressure to arrive). You overcame it twice—once by deviating north at Red Table, again by landing at Eagle instead of pressing to Rifle. Each time, you chose the safe airport over the closer airport.

Key lesson: The nearest airport is not always the best airport. Eagle County is longer-term famous in GA community forums for being exactly the right choice in situations like this—safe, accessible, with ground transport options to your final destination. The shuttle exists specifically because pilots with fuel and weather situations need a way to get over the last 40 miles safely.

Key takeaway: When the weather blocks your original destination, the correct response is not to find another route around it. It's to land at the nearest safe airport and reassess. You landed at Eagle. You waited for better weather. You used ground transport for the last leg. You arrived safely and on time. That's exactly how this is supposed to work.
</div>

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
	_step
<</for>>

<<link "Return to Start" "Opening">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: A2b-TryRifle [scenario branch-a]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" loop volume 0.3 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "atc-ambience" loop volume 0.08 play>><</if>>

You level off and continue west along the Eagle River valley. The valley is wide here, the ceiling high and broken at twelve thousand or so. The ride smooths the further you get from the ridgeline weather. Twenty-five minutes and you're approaching Rifle.

The terrain is dropping. The valley opens toward the Colorado River plateau. The weather that was piled up to the south is still there, still building, but you've got more room down here. Better alternates.

Rifle ASOS: winds two-seven-zero at two-two, gusting three-six.

You do the math in your head immediately. Runway 08/26. Wind from 270 is a direct ninety-degree crosswind. Twenty-two knots sustained, thirty-six knots gust. The 182's demonstrated crosswind component is fifteen knots. You're looking at a gust component more than double that.

Below you, looking down the Roaring Fork Valley toward Aspen from here: mixed conditions. The first ten miles or so look open—the valley is visible, terrain is passable, you could probably descend under the weather and work your way that direction. Beyond ten miles, the valley narrows. The ceiling drops. Terrain rises. At about twenty miles out, the valley disappears into gray. That's where the weather is sitting.

Two realistic options from here.

<<link "A2b-Land. Land at Rifle in the gusty crosswind. You're an experienced pilot. The runway is seven thousand feet long and one hundred feet wide. You've handled gusty crosswinds before—not quite this gusty, but you know how to crab and slip. It's challenging but manageable." "A2b-LandRifle">>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed at Rifle Municipal in 36-knot gust crosswind")])>>
<</link>>

<<link "A2b-Return. The crosswind is too much for comfort. You're not in a racing situation. Burn the fuel and fly back to Eagle where the runway is better aligned for today's wind. Safe and professional." "A2b-GoAroundEagle">>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Returned to Eagle County, gave up Rifle approach")])>>
<</link>>

:: A2b-LandRifle [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" loop volume 0.3 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "atc-ambience" loop volume 0.08 play>><</if>>

You key the radio.

"Rifle, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, inbound from the northeast, requesting landing runway twenty-six."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrol, right traffic for twenty-six, winds two-seven-zero at twenty-two, gusting three-six, altimeter three-zero-one-four."

You set up the approach. Descending, slowing. The PAPI guides you down. You're crabbing twenty degrees into the wind on final—the whole airplane is sideways to the runway but the ground track is straight. That's the crab angle needed to hold the centerline against a steady crosswind.

But crosswind gusts don't stay steady.

At fifty feet, a gust rolls the 182 to the right—your hands are fast, firm aileron correction back to wings level, nose slightly left. The airplane settles. Your eyes are sharp. You can feel the wind pushing you in real time.

At the threshold, you transition from the crab to the slip. Right wing low, left rudder applied. You're lined up with the runway now, the airplane is sideways to your direction of travel, but your centerline is aligned. The right main gear touches down smooth. Transition complete. Left main follows. Nosewheel touches easy.

On rollout, a gust shoves you toward the left edge of the runway—you're ready for it, firm right rudder, a touch of brake, keep the nosewheel straight. The 182 settles into the center stripe.

You've landed in a 36-knot gust crosswind in a 182. Not textbook perfect. But solid technique and better judgment.

Not pretty. Not dangerous. Just... demanding. The kind of landing that makes you glad for every hour you've logged.

Rachel was watching through the cabin window. As the prop winds down, she says, "That was sideways."

"That's what crosswind means."

"I trust you. But maybe warn me next time."

You smile but you don't answer. Your hands are still a little shaky.

The FBO arranges a rental car. It's an hour and forty-five minutes through Glenwood Canyon to Aspen. You arrive at 1:30 PM. Not the earliest, but well before the rehearsal dinner.

Halfway through the canyon, a thunderstorm drops hail on the rental car. Rachel watches it pound the windshield and looks at you.

"Was that the valley you were thinking about flying through?"

Yes. Yes it was.

You wouldn't have made it.


<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: Challenging Crosswind Landings and Risk Tolerance</strong>

You made one initial error—continuing direct toward Red Table when the weather was deteriorating. The recovery was good: deviate north to Eagle. But then you made a second decision that required real skill: you flew onward to Rifle and landed in conditions that were at the absolute edge of the 182's demonstrated capability.

This outcome reveals something important about your flying: you know your limits and you're willing to push them when the alternative is worse. The Roaring Fork Valley approach from Rifle's altitude would have been CFIT waiting to happen—descending into a narrowing, lowering valley with deteriorating visibility is a trap that kills pilots. The hail that hit the rental car halfway through Glenwood Canyon confirms this. You made the right call staying VFR and landing.

But here's the uncomfortable truth: you were cutting it close. 36-knot crosswind gusts are not routine. The 182's demonstrated capability is 15 knots. Demonstrated doesn't mean impossible beyond that—it means "we tested it there and it was okay." But at 36 knots, you're in the realm where a stronger gust, a slightly slower approach, or a tiny error becomes a ground loop or a runway excursion.

You handled it perfectly. Your crab angle was good, your transition to the slip was smooth, your corrective inputs on rollout were precise. This is what currency and skill look like. But it was also close to being a bad outcome, not through lack of skill but through the narrow margin between "challenging landing" and "off the runway."

Key insight: The decision chain that led here was: continue direct (error) → deviate to Eagle (good) → press on to Rifle (neutral to slightly risky) → execute a challenging crosswind landing (correct, given the alternatives). Each choice was defensible at the time. The cumulative effect was that you ended up in a situation that required professional-level crosswind technique.

The alternative was obvious: go back to Eagle, where the runway alignment was better and the wind was manageable. That would have been equally safe and less demanding. You chose the harder path because it kept you moving toward your destination.

Hazardous attitudes: Get-there-itis influenced this decision. The wedding was in Aspen, not Rifle. But the underlying attitude that made the Rifle approach possible is actually the correct one: don't avoid challenges that you're qualified for. A 500-1000 hour pilot in a 182 *should* be able to handle crosswind landings. The problem comes when pilots mistake "should be able to" for "can always do, even in gusts that exceed demonstrated capability."

Key lesson: Crosswind technique is essential mountain flying currency. The afternoon winds in Colorado are not optional—they're the standard condition. If 20-30 knot crosswind gusts make you uncomfortable, the answer is not to avoid them. It's to build skill and currency until they become routine. But there's a difference between "challenging but doable" and "beyond my capability." You flew 36-knot gusts successfully, but that's not an endorsement to start flying 45-knot gusts.

Key takeaway: Know your crosswind limits and practice them. A long, wide runway in calm conditions is how you build the skill. Once you have that skill, you can use it when the situation demands it. But always maintain a margin. Always have a go-around plan. And always understand that there's a ceiling to what you can do safely, even if you have the skill to do it. At 36-knot gusts, you were at that ceiling. You handled it. But next time, going back to Eagle would have been equally valid.
</div>

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
	_step
<</for>>

<<link "Return to Start" "Opening">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>

