:: A2b-GoAroundEagle [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" loop volume 0.3 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "atc-ambience" loop volume 0.1 play>><</if>>

You look at the Rifle windsock, standing straight out from the pole and perpendicular to the runway, and make the call.

"Rifle, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, we're going to decline landing at this time. Heading back toward Eagle."

There's a slight pause. The controller knows what that means.

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrol, roger. Frequency change back to Denver Center approved. Have a good day."

Rachel feels the bank as you turn back northeast.

"Not landing there?"

"Crosswind is too much. We'll go back to Eagle."

She nods. She didn't see the windsock but she can feel the wind pushing the airplane around at altitude. The decision makes sense to her.

The flight back to Eagle takes twenty-five minutes. You've now been flying for nearly two hours and you've accomplshed nothing except a detailed tour of western Colorado. The ground below has changed from the Front Range foothills to the Eagle River valley and back to the Eagle River valley, which is not where you wanted to be.

Fuel totalizer: thirty-nine gallons. Still plenty—you've got two and a half hours of endurance remaining. But eighteen gallons of that went to go from Eagle to Rifle and back. That's a thousand-dollar lesson in wind.

Eagle County tower clears you for landing on runway 24. The wind here is 270 at 19 gusting 28—manageable, a light crosswind component. You land without drama.

It's 11:15 AM.

The shuttle to Aspen has already left. The next one departs at 2:00 PM. You'll arrive in Aspen by 3:30 PM. The rehearsal dinner is at 7:00 PM. Tight, but fine.

You park at Signature and Rachel sits in the FBO lounge with her coffee, looking out at the weather still building over the ridge to the south.

"We could have been here two hours ago," she says.

She's right.

You don't have a good answer. The decision to reject the Rifle crosswind wasn't wrong. The winds there were at the edge of your comfort zone, and your instinct to reject them was sound. But the cost of that conservatism was two hours of flying and eighteen gallons of fuel.

The question for your own personal debrief: Was the Rifle crosswind beyond your capability, or just beyond your comfort?


<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: Conservatism vs. Capability</strong>

You made one initial error—continuing direct toward Red Table—and then you executed a good recovery: deviate north to Eagle. From there, you pressed on to Rifle, assessed the conditions, and made a conservative choice to turn back.

This is where the debrief gets uncomfortable, because conservatism is a virtue in aviation, but there's a difference between healthy caution and risk aversion that costs you.

The Rifle crosswind was 36-knot gusts. The 182's demonstrated crosswind component is 15 knots. By the numbers, that's more than double. By the facts, though: a 500-1000 hour pilot in a 182 should be able to handle 25-30 knot crosswind gusts under normal conditions. Most part 135 operators regularly fly in 20-knot crosswind components. The issue at Rifle wasn't capability—it was comfort.

You rejected the landing because it was challenging. That's a valid personal decision. Some pilots have lower wind tolerance, some have higher. But the cost of that decision was real: two hours of flight time, eighteen gallons of Avgas, a late arrival (though still in time for dinner), and the knowledge that you could have made it if you'd pushed yourself a bit.

The question for your personal pilot record: Did you grow as a pilot today, or did you retreat from a challenge that was within your skill envelope?

Both answers are defensible. Aviation has buried plenty of pilots who pushed themselves beyond their limits. It's also buried a few who were so conservative they never developed the skills to handle real-world weather. The trick is knowing which category you're in.

Evidence: You descended into low visibility toward a narrowing valley as an alternative. That's less safe than a crosswind landing on a long, wide runway. The hail in Glenwood Canyon that hit the rental car confirms this—the weather you were trying to avoid was real and serious.

Key lesson: There's a difference between "challenging" and "dangerous." A 36-knot crosswind gust is challenging. It's not dangerous for a pilot with 500-1000 hours who practices crosswind landings regularly. It's only dangerous if you don't know how to handle it. If you don't know how to handle 30-knot crosswind gusts, that's your training gap, not the wind's problem. Fix the training.

The decision to turn back was professionally sound. But the fuel and time cost reveals something about your risk tolerance. Some pilots would have landed. Some wouldn't have. There's no single right answer—only the answer that's right for your training, experience, and comfort.

Hazardous attitudes: Risk aversion here was protective (good) but also expensive. You might have been influenced by the phrase "demonstrated crosswind component"—which is regulatory language that can feel like a hard limit. It's not. It's a minimum assurance that the airplane can handle that wind. Beyond that, it depends on skill.

Key takeaway: Evaluate your own crosswind skill honestly. If 36-knot gusts are beyond you, that's fine—you made the right call at Rifle. But then make that your training target. Crosswind landings are not something you can ignore in mountain flying. Colorado winds are not optional. Build the skill in calm conditions so that when the weather situation demands it (as it did today), you have the option to use it. Don't let wind surprise you. Don't let a long runway and skilled technique be wasted because you've never practiced them together.
</div>

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
	_step
<</for>>

