:: A2c-HoldEagle [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" loop volume 0.3 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "atc-ambience" loop volume 0.1 play>><</if>>

You set up an orbit over the Eagle River valley at twelve thousand five hundred feet. The view is actually beautiful—the valley spread below, I-70 threading through it, the mountains on either side. The weather to the south is still piling up, but maybe—just maybe—it's starting to move.

You give it twenty minutes.

The weather doesn't improve. In fact, it gets worse. The line from Vail Pass to Independence Pass that was solid before is now even more solid. The tops are above you now—anvil cores reaching toward 30,000. You're watching organized convection at its peak.

Ten minutes later, Aspen updates: winds two-two-zero at fourteen gusting twenty-four, visibility two miles in rain, broken at five-thousand AGL, with occasional lower. Trending down. The weather isn't moving east. It's moving north, toward Aspen.

Rachel, who's been quiet during the orbits: "It's been twenty minutes. Is it getting better?"

"No."

"So what are we doing?"

You look at the fuel totalizer. Forty gallons remaining. You've burned six gallons of fuel in these orbits—fuel that didn't accomplish anything except hope.

There's no good answer to her question. The weather isn't cooperating. The only response now is to accept that and land.

You call Eagle County tower.

"Eagle, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrol, request descent into Eagle. We'll land."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrol, clear to land runway twenty-four. Winds two-seven-zero at nineteen gusting twenty-eight."

You spiral down and land at 11:15 AM. Forty-five minutes later than if you'd landed on the first pass overhead Eagle.

The shuttle's gone. The next one leaves at 2:00 PM. You'll arrive in Aspen at 3:30 PM. Tight for the 7:00 PM dinner.

Rachel doesn't say anything about the wasted time. She doesn't need to. You both understand what holding those twenty minutes cost.


<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: Hope Is Not a Strategy</strong>

You made one good decision (deviate north from Red Table) and one decision shaped by hope instead of planning: the hold over Eagle.

This is a common trap in mountain flying, especially in summer when conditions can change quickly. The instinct is: "I've come this far. The weather might move. Summer storms don't last long. Let me give it a few minutes."

But here's what holding does: nothing good. You had the information you needed on the first pass overhead Eagle. The wall was established. Multiple aircraft were already diverting. Aspen was deteriorating, not improving. The conditions on your second pass overhead (after 20 minutes of orbiting) were identical or worse.

Holding cost you: six gallons of fuel (at today's Avgas prices, about $30), twenty minutes of flight time, and a slightly delayed arrival in Aspen.

More importantly, it cost you something psychological: the reinforcement of a bad habit. If you hold and the weather improves, you're trained to try again next time. If you hold and it doesn't improve (as in this case), you're trained to waste fuel and time. The lose-lose situation, disguised as a strategy.

The correct approach to a weather wall: identify it, evaluate it, and make the go/no-go decision based on the information you have. One orbit for situational assessment is reasonable. Two minutes of close observation is okay. Twenty minutes is denial.

Key insight: You should have set a decision gate before you started holding. "I'll orbit for five minutes. If the weather doesn't show improvement, I'm landing." Then execute that plan. The problem with holding is that it's always subjective. "One more orbit. Just one more. Maybe the next pass will be different." But the weather doesn't move faster because you're watching it. It moves at the speed it's going to move.

You had alternatives. Eagle County was directly below, with a long runway and good terrain. Rifle was 38 miles away with a manageable wind if you turned back. Neither alternative was attractive (you'd already flown to both), but they were available. The smartest move would have been to land on the first pass overhead Eagle and accept that Aspen would come via ground transport.

Hazardous attitudes: This is primarily an error of "wishful thinking" or "normalization of risk." Summer storms *do* move fast. But this one wasn't moving your direction. You were normalizing risk based on the general pattern, not the specific situation.

Key lesson: Set decision gates before you need them. "I'll hold for five minutes" is a plan. "I'll hold until the weather improves" is hope. Hope is not a strategy. Plan your holds. Execute your plans. Don't let the weather dictate your decisions through passive waiting.

Key takeaway: When you're overhead a safe airport and the destination weather is questionable, land. It takes maturity to accept that you've come 85 miles west only to land 40 miles short of your destination. But that's what professional pilots do. You land. You refuel. You wait for better conditions or you arrange ground transport. The airplane isn't winning awards for arriving last. It's winning awards for arriving at all, and arriving safely.
</div>

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
	_step
<</for>>

<<link "Return to Start" "Opening">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: A3-PushGap [scenario branch-a]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" loop volume 0.3 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "wind-turbulence" loop volume 0.25 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-rough" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>

You push toward the closing gap. It's maybe three miles wide now, and you can see the sunlit terrain on the other side—the Roaring Fork Valley, green, accessible. Fifteen minutes. You can make it through. You can do this.

The gap tightens as you fly toward it. The cells on either side are definitely merging, the rain shafts are more visible, the cloud bases are visibly lower. But there's still a gap. The sunlit terrain is still visible through it. You can do this.

Two miles to the gap now.

The downdraft hits without warning. Not turbulence. Downdraft. The VSI needle doesn't just drop—it pegs at minus eighteen hundred feet per minute. The altimeter unwinds: 14,000... 13,500... 13,000. You've lost a thousand feet of altitude in about thirty seconds and you're still descending.

You push the yoke forward and add full power. The 182 pitches down slightly as you pour everything the engine has into fighting. RPM climbs. Engine temperatures climb. Manifold pressure needle climbs. Everything is in the green but it's all red hot.

The downdraft doesn't care.

Altitude: 12,500... 12,000. Still descending at 1,800 fpm despite full power.

Rain transitions from streaks to sheets. Visibility vanishes. The gap you could see is gone. The light ahead is gone. The world is gray.

G1000 synth vision pops up and shows ridgelines on both sides, at altitude, rising. The terrain is around 11,000. You're at 12,000 and descending toward 11,000, and the synth vision is painting mountains on both sides.

The turbulence turns severe. Not moderate turbulence. Not "hold the coffee." Severe. The 182 is being thrown. Your hands are tight on the yoke, fighting just to keep it level. Rachel's hands are white on the armrest and she's making sounds that might be prayers or might be screams—you can't tell.

IMC. Mountains on both sides. Severe turbulence. Downdraft you can't out-climb. No visibility. No good options.

The radio crackles. "Traffic, traffic, traffic..." is all you hear before it cuts out.

Two paths ahead. Only two.

<<link "A3a. Declare MAYDAY immediately. Tell Denver Center you are IMC in the mountains in a severe downdraft, unable to maintain altitude. Request immediate vectors to lower terrain. Mayday is not a failure. It's a tool." "A3a-DeclareEmergency">>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Declared MAYDAY, severe downdraft in mountains, IMC"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "A3b. Focus on climbing. You need altitude to get out of this. Full power, nose up, push hard and try to climb above the weather. You've got to get higher." "A3b-ClimbAbove">>
	<<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
	<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Attempted to climb above downdraft in mountainous terrain"])>>
<</link>>

:: A3a-DeclareEmergency [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "mayday-declaration" play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-rough" loop volume 0.15 play>><</if>>

Your hand is steady. Years of training take over. You key the radio.

"Denver Center, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, MAYDAY MAYDAY MAYDAY. I am IMC in the mountains, in a severe downdraft, unable to maintain altitude. Requesting immediate vectors to lower terrain."

There's a pause—less than a second but it feels like an hour. Then:

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger MAYDAY. Turn right heading three-five-zero immediately. Eagle River valley is to your north. Minimum vectoring altitude one-four thousand but I show terrain to thirteen thousand within five miles of your position. Advise your current altitude."

"Twelve thousand two hundred and descending," you read off. Your voice is steady.

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, fly heading three-five-zero. Advise when you have visual contact with the ground or change in conditions."

You fly the heading. Right turn, rolling out on 350, flying by instruments only. The gray doesn't break. The turbulence doesn't ease. But you're flying toward something—north, toward the valley, toward lower terrain, toward somewhere that isn't between two mountains at cloud altitude.

Four minutes. It feels like an hour.

Then the rain lightens. A shade of gray lighter than it was. The turbulence eases a fraction.

At eleven thousand four hundred feet, the gray breaks to scattered clouds. Below you: the Eagle River valley. Wide. Green. I-70 visible threading along the river. The valley floor is about six thousand feet. You're at eleven thousand and there's nothing but air and valley between you and safety.

"Denver Center, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, visual, Eagle valley in sight, request Eagle County airport."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger, visual confirmed. Eagle County airport ten miles on your left. Altitude you are now good. Squawk VFR, frequency change approved to Eagle County. Well done."

You change frequency and call Eagle County. They clear you to land. The approach is calm. Smooth. The landing is uneventful—the most beautiful uneventful landing you've ever made.

You taxi in and the tower says, "Good landing, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrol. Welcome to Eagle County."

You park the 182. You shut down. You sit for a moment without saying anything.

Rachel's hands are still gripping the armrest. Her voice is very quiet.

"I am never doing that again," she says. "Can we drive?"

You nod. There's nothing to say. You nearly died together and your instinct to stay alive overrode your instinct to stay flying. That's the right order of priorities.


<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: CFIT Recognition and Emergency Response</strong>

This outcome required an emergency declaration in IMC in mountainous terrain—the most dangerous flying environment there is. Statistically, you should not have survived. But you did, because of one decision: the immediate MAYDAY call.

Let's be clear about what happened: you flew into convection that you shouldn't have entered. You then flew between closing cells at an altitude where surrounding terrain was at or above your flight level. And then you got caught in a downdraft that was stronger than anything your airplane could overcome. At that point, the emergency was already happening. The only question was whether you would recognize it.

You did. You declared MAYDAY. You didn't waste time or altitude trying to fix the unfixable. You asked for help. You flew the heading the controller gave you. You got to lower terrain.

Key insight: The decision chain that led to this emergency was: (1) Continue direct toward Red Table—error. (2) Push into closing gap between cells—major error. Each of these was a clear warning sign. By the time you were in the downdraft, all your options were bad. The only one that wasn't terminal was the emergency declaration.

Here's what you didn't do—and why it matters: You didn't attempt to climb above the weather. The instinct to climb when you're trapped in the mountains is natural and it kills pilots. The downdraft you were in exceeded three thousand feet per minute. Full power in a 182 at high density altitude produces maybe five hundred to seven hundred feet per minute of climb. You were being pushed down faster than you could climb up. Any attempt to out-climb this would have burned fuel and altitude and ended in Controlled Flight Into Terrain.

Instead, you flew the heading toward lower terrain. That was the only winning move.

Hazardous attitudes: This entire outcome traces back to continued VFR flight into IMC in mountainous terrain, the first decision that continued direct, the second decision that pushed into the gap. These are documented killer attitudes: get-there-itis (the wedding in Aspen), continued expectancy (the Baron made it, so you could too), and normalization of risk (other traffic is still diverting, not turning back).

Key lesson: The gap between cells at altitude is a trap. It looks safe from a distance because you can see through it. But gap closure can outrun any airplane's ability to exit. Once you're in a gap between cells, the gap can merge before you get through it. At that point, you're in between two weather systems with limited visibility, terrain around you, and limited escape routes.

The FAA recommends maintaining at least 20 miles from any thunderstorm. You attempted to fly between cells separated by less than 4 miles. That was the core error.

Key takeaway: If you find yourself declaring MAYDAY in the mountains, understand that you made errors long before the radio call. The emergency was survivable because you recognized it and asked for help. But the decisions that created it were not defensible. Never push into closing gaps between cells. Never expect to out-climb a mountain thunderstorm downdraft. And always have a go-to-lower-terrain plan, because the weather is always stronger than your airplane.

The fact that you survived is a gift. Learn from the errors that led here so that you never have to make this decision again.
</div>

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
	_step
<</for>>

<<link "Return to Start" "Opening">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: A3b-ClimbAbove [scenario branch-a ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-rough" loop volume 0.2 play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "stall-horn" play>><</if>>

You pull back on the yoke. Full power is already set. The 182 pitches up.

Airspeed bleeds: 100... 95... 90 knots. At this density altitude, at this weight, you're producing maybe sixty-five percent power. Maybe. The rate-of-climb indicator, which was at minus 1,800, shifts to minus 900. Progress. Not enough progress.

Airspeed: 80 knots.

The stall horn chirps once. A warning. You relax back pressure slightly, trade altitude for airspeed. The horn stops.

Airspeed: 75 knots.

The downdraft is constant. Unrelenting. The altimeter unwinds: 11,000... 10,500. Still descending despite full power, despite maximum climb attitude, despite everything the 182 has to give.

The rain is opaque. The turbulence is severe. The G1000 synthetic vision flashes red in multiple places. Terrain, terrain everywhere.

Airspeed: 70 knots. Too slow. You have to push forward or you'll stall. So you push forward. The nose lowers. Descent rate increases. Altitude loss accelerates.

Altimeter: 10,200 feet. Mountains are around 11,000. The gap is closing.

The last thing the crew will report is that the wreckage was found on the west slope of a 12,600-foot ridge, approximately two miles south of the V-8 airway centerline. The aircraft impacted terrain in a shallow right bank. Both occupants sustained fatal injuries.

The weather that day: embedded thunderstorms with tops above 35,000 feet, severe turbulence, heavy precipitation, and updrafts in excess of 3,000 feet per minute downdraft.

Probable cause: the pilot's continued VFR flight into known adverse weather and mountainous terrain, the decision to penetrate convection knowing the weather was deteriorating, and the fatal decision to attempt to climb above a mature thunderstorm cell at high density altitude.

The Cessna 182 cannot out-climb a thunderstorm downdraft. No piston single can.


<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: CFIT — Fatal Outcome Analysis</strong>

This is the worst outcome in the scenario. Three compounding errors led here:

**Error One — Continue Direct (Early Scenario):** When the weather at Red Table was deteriorating and alternatives existed (deviation north to Eagle, climb to higher altitude, contact Flight Service for updated weather), you chose to continue direct. This was driven by get-there-itis and normalized risk ("the Baron made it, so can I").

**Error Two — Push Into Closing Gap:** When the gap between cells began to merge and the cumulus developed to towering level, you chose to push through rather than deviate. This was the fatal commitment. The gap closure happened faster than you could exit. By the time you were in the gap, the gap was closing.

**Error Three — Attempt to Climb in Downdraft:** This was the terminal decision. When caught in severe downdraft, the instinct is to climb. This is the wrong instinct in mountain flying. A downdraft stronger than 1,000 fpm cannot be out-climbed by a piston single. The attempt to climb burned fuel, bled airspeed, and accelerated altitude loss. The correct response would have been to declare MAYDAY immediately and ask for vectors to lower terrain.

But you didn't make that decision. You tried to out-climb.

Key insight: Every one of these errors had a warning sign:

- Red Table deterioration: Cumulus that was scattered at the briefing is now towering. Citation reported severe turbulence and hail. The gap is visibly closing. These are all "go-around now" signals.

- Gap closure: The gap that was 8 miles wide is now 4 miles wide. The cell tops are above you. The rain shafts are visible. This is "exit immediately" information.

- Downdraft: The VSI pegs at minus 1,800. Altimeter unwinds at 1,000 fpm rate. This is "declare emergency now" information.

At every stage, the correct action was clear. At no stage did you take it.

Hazardous attitudes: Continued expectancy ("the Baron made it"), get-there-itis (the wedding), normalization of risk ("other traffic is still in the area"). These are the attitudes that kill GA pilots. The data supports this: the top causes of GA accidents in mountainous terrain are:

1. VFR into IMC
2. Continued flight into deteriorating weather
3. Attempted terrain avoidance in IMC
4. CFIT in convection

You experienced all four.

Key lesson: The margin between survivable and fatal in mountain flying is measured in minutes and miles. The difference between this outcome and the MAYDAY outcome above is one decision: declare the emergency instead of attempting to climb.

Declare. Don't climb. Declare and fly the heading to lower terrain.

Key takeaway: This outcome is not inevitable. It's entirely preventable at multiple decision points:

- At the opening, request updated weather and climb to 16,500 to maintain VFR above developing weather.
- At Red Table deterioration, deviate immediately north to Eagle County. Don't press.
- If you do press and get caught in downdraft, declare MAYDAY immediately. Ask for lower terrain vectors. Fly the heading. Don't try to out-climb.

The Cessna 182 is a good airplane. It will do what you ask it to do. But it will not climb 3,000 feet per minute in a downdraft. No airplane will. When you're caught in that, the only winning move is to ask for help and fly to lower terrain.

If you've been following this scenario with the assumption that "I would have made different decisions," consider this: every pilot who died in this exact scenario probably thought the same thing. The difference between survivors and fatalities in mountain flying is recognizing the warning signs early and acting on them, not on skill or aircraft capability.

Act early. Deviate early. Declare early. Don't wait until the emergency is terminal.
</div>

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
	_step
<</for>>

