:: B-DeviateNorth [scenario branch-b]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Deviated north toward Eagle County"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "radio-squelch" play>><</if>>

You key the mic. "Denver Center, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot. Request deviation north toward the Eagle County corridor. Weather building along the Divide."

"Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, Denver. Approved, deviation north. Heading zero-three-zero. Climb maintain one-four-five-hundred."

"Zero-three-zero, one-four-five-hundred. Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot."

You bank right, firmly, 30 degrees. The turbulence is sharp through the turn but manageable. The buildups along the Continental Divide—those dark, anvil-shaped towers over the Sawatch Range and Red Table—slip behind your left wing. They're concentrated over the highest terrain, where the air has nowhere to go but up. To the north, though, the Gore Range is lower. The cells are more scattered. You can see it: a visible corridor along the Eagle River valley, open sky, a passage through.

Rachel leans closer to the windscreen. "How bad is it down there?"

"Bad enough that we're not going that way."

Thirty minutes later, you're overhead Eagle County VOR at 14,500 feet. The valley below spreads out in clear relief—the Eagle River a thin silver line, I-70 snaking through the flattest part, the town of Eagle itself a gridwork of streets nestled against the rising terrain. This is good country. You've made the right call heading here.

But then you look south, toward Aspen, and your stomach tightens.

A solid line of buildups has formed between you and your destination. Not scattered cells. Not breaks. A wall. A line that runs from Vail Pass southwest toward Independence Pass, dark bases around 12,000 feet, tops reaching well above your altitude. The rain shafts are visible even from here—gray curtains hanging from the clouds, some of them clearly reaching the ground.

Rachel sees it too. "That doesn't look great."

"No," you agree. "It doesn't."

You call Center. "Denver, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot. Request current weather picture between Eagle and Aspen. Also Rifle."

A pause. Then: "Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, I'm painting a solid line of moderate to heavy returns from Vail Pass southwest toward Independence Pass. Bases appear to be around one-two-thousand. Tops well above flight level. Multiple aircraft have reported diverting today. Aspen is reporting scattered thunderstorms to the north of the airport."

You acknowledge and work the G1000. Aspen is 38 miles south-southeast of your current position. Rifle is 38 miles west. Eagle is directly below you. Fuel state: 48 gallons remaining. Endurance: 4 hours at this power setting. You have options, but the clock is ticking and so is the weather.

Rachel's fingers are drumming on the armrest—a sign you've learned to recognize as mild anxiety. "What are you thinking?"

You have three options, and you know it:

<<link "Land at Eagle — the weather's a wall between here and Aspen." "B1-LandEagle">>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Descending to Eagle County"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "Continue west to Rifle, then approach Aspen from the northwest through the Roaring Fork Valley." "B2-ContinueRifle">>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continuing west to Rifle"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "Try to find a gap in the weather and go south toward Aspen." "B3-TrySouth">>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Attempting to go south through the weather"])>>
<<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>

:: B1-LandEagle [scenario branch-b]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Descending to Eagle County"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "radio-squelch" play>><</if>>

"Denver, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot. We're going to request descent into Eagle."

"Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, descent approved. Descend and maintain niner thousand. Eagle County frequency is one-two-one point two. Good day."

You call Eagle County tower, report 12 miles northwest, request left downwind for runway 25. The controller clears you and adds, almost as an afterthought: "Wind is currently two-seven-zero at two-two, gusting three-two. Runway two-five is the active. Fair warning—wind shear reported in the pattern."

Windshear. Of course. The mountain winds in the afternoon are never steady—they bounce off the ridgelines, create rotors, shift direction in the space of a few hundred feet. You've handled worse, but not often.

As you descend through 11,000 feet, the wind in the valleys picks up noticeably. The 182 starts getting buffeted. Not rough air from convection now—mechanical turbulence, pure and simple. The ridgelines around Eagle are funneling the wind, accelerating it, creating shear.

You enter the pattern at 2,500 feet. The windsock is standing straight out—nearly horizontal. That's 22 knots with gusts to 32. You do the math: runway 25, wind 270. That's a roughly 20-degree crosswind component. Manageable for a 182, which has a demonstrated crosswind component of 12.3 knots. But demonstrated is a test condition on a calm day with a smooth pilot. You're neither calm nor smooth right now—you're a real pilot in real wind, and the 182 is a forgiving airplane.

On downwind, a gust rocks the right wing hard. You lose 200 feet before you catch it with trim and a firm back pressure. Rachel's hand shoots out to brace herself. "Still okay back there?" you ask.

"Still here," she says, not entirely convincingly.

On base, the wind shifts. Now it's coming more from the southwest, 250 degrees. That changes the crosswind component—it's more direct now, more perpendicular to the runway. You increase your crab angle. The approach is beginning to feel uncoordinated, like you're constantly playing catch-up with the wind.

On final, the PAPI shows you're high. Too high. But you know what's happening—it's the downdraft on final approach. Mountain airports do this: the wind flows over the ridge on the upwind side of the runway, creates a descending column of air, and it hits you on approach. You add power, trying to maintain your glide path. The altimeter shows 500 feet above the runway. 300. The wind gusts again, and the airplane yaws.

This landing is going to test you. You can feel it.

<<link "Commit to the approach—manage the crosswind, get it done." "B1a-CommitLanding">>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Committed to the approach"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "Go around and try one more circuit—the wind will settle." "B1b-GoAround">>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Went around for another circuit"])>>
<<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>

:: B1a-CommitLanding [scenario branch-b ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" stop>><<audio "touchdown" play>><</if>>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed safely at Eagle County"])>>

You commit. The airplane is stable, your approach is established, and adding power for one more circuit is only going to cost you fuel, fatigue, and confidence. You're going to fly this one down.

The PAPI goes from four white lights to two white, two red as you add power through the downdraft zone. Your airspeed is holding steady at 75 knots—you're carrying an extra 5 knots for the gusts, and the heavier airplane is helping you cut through the turbulence. At 100 feet above the ground, a gust from the left hits hard and rolls you 15 degrees, wing down. Immediate opposite rudder, back on the yoke, correction back to centerline. Your eyes are on the runway numbers.

At 50 feet, you transition to what every crosswind landing requires: crab and kick. You crab the airplane into the wind, nose pointed left toward the mountains, fuselage angled toward the northwest. The runway is dead ahead. At 20 feet, you kick the nose straight with right rudder and flare. The upwind main gear touches first—firm but not hard. The downwind main follows a tenth of a second later. The nosewheel comes down last, and you're on the pavement, rolling, the wind still trying to push you sideways but the wheels are doing their job now.

You apply gentle forward pressure, maintain centerline with differential braking, and let the 182 slow. The windsock blurs past the right wing. Rolling, rolling, slowing. At 30 knots, the wind is no longer a threat. You're down.

Eagle County's 9,000-foot runway is more than enough. You taxi toward Signature Aviation, the FBO, and pull into a spot on the ramp. You shut down the engines and sit in the sudden silence. Your hands are shaking slightly—adrenaline, nothing more—and your shirt is damp with sweat. A good landing. A landing that required work. Exactly what you needed.

Rachel unbuckles and leans forward between the seats. Her face is flushed, her eyes wide. "That approach was... interesting."

"Mountain airports in the afternoon," you say, reaching for the first shutdown checklist item.

"Is it always like that?"

"More often than you'd think. But today was solid. The first approach was our best chance, and we took it."

She nods slowly, processing. "I'm glad you didn't go around."

You meet her eyes. "So am I."


The FBO line crew meets you at the airplane with chocks and a water bottle. You secure the 182, file a flight plan cancellation with Denver, and arrange the ground shuttle to Aspen. It's 10:30 AM. The shuttle runs hourly. The next one departs at 11:00.

The drive down I-70 is scenic—the valley opens up, terrain drops away, and by the time you're in Glenwood Canyon, you can see clear sky to the south. The weather wall is behind you now, a thing you passed around instead of into.

You arrive at the Aspen venue at 12:30 PM. The rehearsal dinner setup is in full swing—caterers, florists, the band testing speakers. Ben sees you both and his face breaks into a grin. He jogs over, embraces you both. "You made it! I heard the weather was crazy over the Divide. Seriously, I wasn't sure you were going to make it."

"The weather was interesting," you say.

Rachel puts a hand on your shoulder. "Your friend is a very careful pilot." She says it like a compliment, and Ben's eyes widen slightly with new appreciation.

"Is he really?"

"He is. He deviates when he needs to, he assesses every situation, and he commits when the time comes. That's careful."


<div class="debrief">
<strong>DEBRIEF: A Strong Outcome</strong>

This is a strong outcome. Your initial deviation north toward Eagle County was a sound strategic decision—you recognized the developing weather as you approached the Continental Divide, chose the path with lighter conditions, and executed the plan without second-guessing. When the wall of weather between Eagle and Aspen proved impassable, you landed at the nearest suitable airport without hesitation. No wasted time. No holding and hoping. No shopping for better options.

The gusty crosswind landing at Eagle required solid technique but was entirely within the aircraft's demonstrated capabilities and well within your actual skill level. You flew the approach with a plan—crab and kick on final—and you committed to it. The wind was manageable, the runway was large, and you executed.

<strong>Key Strength:</strong> You deviated early, assessed the picture at Eagle, and committed to landing when the information was clear. The deviation north was a strategy, not a detour. You weren't running from the weather—you were positioning yourself at the best available alternate while maintaining options.

<strong>Cost and Reward:</strong> Eagle to Aspen is 90 minutes by shuttle. That's the price of good judgment—not expensive, in the grand scheme of decisions made at 14,500 feet. The reward is an intact airplane, a living passenger, and a story you tell over drinks, not one you tell to the NTSB.

</div>


<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
  _step
<</for>>

