:: B1b-GoAround [scenario branch-b ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" stop>><<audio "touchdown" play>><</if>>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Went around, second approach in worse conditions"])>>

You add full power. The flaps retract from 20 to 0 degrees. The 182's nose comes up and you climb away from the runway, announcing the go-around to the tower. "Eagle tower, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, going around."

"Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, eagle, approved. Left downwind, one-four-five-hundred."

But climbing out of the pattern, you feel it immediately: the turbulence is sharper than it was on the way down. The afternoon has gone on, the mountains have warmed more, and the mechanical turbulence off the ridges has intensified. A gust shoves the right wing hard and you lose your orientation relative to the runway for a moment—just a moment, but long enough to notice. You re-establish left downwind and continue the climb.

You've committed now. The fuel you just burned during the climb-out, the time you spent getting back up to pattern altitude, the fatigue beginning to build in your shoulders and forearms. The wind is not supposed to change in two minutes, but you're hoping anyway. You're hoping the gusts will calm. You're hoping the downdraft will ease. You're hoping the approach will be smoother.

But the Eagle ASOS updates as you level off at pattern altitude: "Eagle County automated weather. Two-seven-zero at two-four, gusting three-four."

The wind has not calmed. It's gotten worse.

You fly the second approach steeper than the first, trying to stay on the PAPI and compensate for what you now know about the downdraft. But the steeper approach and the worse wind combine to work against you. On final, you're fighting to stay on glide path. The wind is stronger, the downdraft is meaner, and you're tired. Your inputs are slightly larger, slightly slower. The approach feels disorganized.

You add power more aggressively than necessary to counter the downdraft, and by the time you're at 50 feet, you're a bit high. You flare and immediately realize you're going to be firm on this landing. The upwind main gear touches with a distinct thump. Not hard enough to be dangerous, but hard enough that you'll want to check the gear later, hard enough that Rachel grips the armrest tighter.

The downwind main follows, then the nosewheel. The wind is still trying to push you around, and you manage it. You're on the pavement, slowing, the crosswind still present but no longer a threat. Rolling, rolling, slowing. You're down safely, but the landing was worse than necessary.

Rachel has been gripping the armrest since the first turbulence. Now she releases it and her hand shakes slightly. "I think I'm done flying for today."

You don't argue.


You make the 11:30 shuttle to Aspen. The drive is scenic but neither of you is talking much. The airplane is fine—you'll check the landing gear in the morning and find no damage, no cracks, no red flags. The landing was firm but not catastrophic. But it was worse than it needed to be, and you both know it.

You arrive at the Aspen venue at 1:00 PM. Ben is in the middle of directing staff on chair placement, and he sees you with obvious relief. "You made it! And you've got time to spare." He doesn't mention the weather, doesn't ask about the flight, just pulls you both into embraces and moves on to wedding logistics.


<div class="debrief">
<strong>DEBRIEF: The Right Maneuver, Wrong Reason</strong>

The go-around itself was executed correctly. There is never anything wrong with executing a go-around when you're not comfortable. Go-arounds are a fundamental tool and a sign of good judgment. But the reason you went around was wrong: you went around hoping the wind would calm, and it didn't. The wind strengthened by 2 knots sustained and 2 knots gust. The result was a more difficult landing in worse conditions, additional fatigue, and burned fuel.

<strong>Key Error:</strong> Mountain winds in the afternoon don't calm down. They build. If the wind is gusting 32 knots and sustained, it's not going to be 28 sustained and 32 gusting three minutes later. The temperature differential between the peaks and the valleys is only increasing as the afternoon progresses. The wind gets worse, not better.

<strong>The Real Lesson:</strong> Commit to your landing when the approach is stable and flyable. Your first approach was your best approach. The wind was the same, the downdraft was the same, your fatigue was less. The go-around didn't prevent a bad landing—it caused one. The landing gear is fine, Rachel will recover, the airplane is safe. But this time you paid a price for the "one more try" thinking. That pattern of behavior—deciding to go around hoping conditions improve—is what accumulates into accident statistics.

<strong>Key Takeaway:</strong> Train yourself to see the approach as either "stable and ready to land" or "something is wrong." If the approach is stable, land. Don't gamble on improvement in mountain valleys. The variance in wind gusts doesn't work in your favor over three minutes.

</div>


