:: B2-ContinueRifle [scenario branch-b]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continuing west to Rifle"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" play>><</if>>

You key the mic. "Denver, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot. Continue westbound, we'll request descent into Rifle."

"Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, roger. Approved westbound. Descend and maintain niner thousand five hundred. Rifle frequency one-two-two point five."

You push the nose forward and the descent begins. Westbound along the Eagle River valley, the terrain below opens up as you lose altitude. The valley is wide here—three, four miles across at points. The ridgelines rise to 11,000 and beyond, but they're not threatening. The air beneath you smooths as you descend. Broken clouds at 12,000 above the valley floor. You descend to 10,500 and the ride gets better.

Rachel is looking down at the valley, at the river, at the small towns along I-70. "This is beautiful country."

"It is," you agree. "And it's more forgiving than what we left behind."

Twenty-five minutes of steady descent, and Rifle appears ahead—a small airport on the high plains, elevation 5,340 feet. A far cry from the mountains. You call the tower. "Rifle tower, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, ten miles northeast, requesting left downwind for two-six."

"Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, Rifle. Welcome. Wind two-seven-zero at two-two, gusting three-six. Runway two-six is the active."

You acknowledge and think about it. Two-two sustained, gusting 36. Runway 08/26. That's a 90-degree crosswind on runway 26, and the gust component is at the edge of your demonstrated crosswind. But Rifle's runway is 7,000 feet long and 100 feet wide—a runway built for larger airplanes, a runway that will forgive a firm landing.

As you descend into the pattern, you get a clear look at the conditions. The wind is visible in the windsock—flag-straight, barely moving, the gusts strong enough to make it oscillate. It's challenging, but Rifle is designed for this. The runway is there. The airport is here.

But something makes you look south. Down the Roaring Fork Valley toward Aspen, the first ten miles look inviting—broken clouds, green valley, the river visible like a ribbon. But further southeast, the valley narrows and the ceiling drops. You can't see Aspen itself. The valley just disappears into gray about twenty miles out.

"Rifle tower, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, left downwind runway two-six."

"Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, Rifle, approve left downwind two-six. Runway two-six is the active."

You have two options now, and the clock is ticking:

<<link "Land at Rifle—accept the crosswind and put the 182 on the runway safely." "B2a-LandRifle">>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landing at Rifle"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "Continue into the Roaring Fork Valley toward Aspen—follow the river, stay low, see if it opens up." "B2b-RoaringFork">>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Entered the Roaring Fork Valley"])>>
<<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>

:: B2a-LandRifle [scenario branch-b ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" stop>><<audio "touchdown" play>><</if>>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed safely at Rifle"])>>

You bring the 182 around on base, descending toward runway 26. The wind is strong from the northwest, and you know it. Rifle tower is clear: "Winds two-seven-zero at two-two, gusting three-six. Runway two-six is the active. Cleared to land."

You roll left toward the runway and start your crosswind correction. Crab angle 25 degrees into the wind. On final, the runway is aligned beneath you. You're high—you add a bit of forward pressure and let gravity do the work. The airspeed is solid at 70 knots. You're not carrying extra speed this time; Rifle is big and flat, and confidence is half the battle.

At 100 feet, the wind shifts momentarily and pushes you right. Immediate left correction—firm, controlled. At 50 feet, a gust from the left rocks the wing down 10 degrees. Right aileron, wings level. You transition to the crab-and-kick: nose pointed left into the wind, fuselage angled, and at 20 feet, you kick the nose straight with right rudder and flare.

The right main tire touches first—solid contact. The left main follows. The nosewheel comes down. You've got all three wheels on the ground, and the wind is trying to push you left. Right rudder, right brake, holding the centerline, the windsock blurring past your right wing. The 182 slows. At 30 knots, you're safely in the grip of the pavement, the wind no longer a threat.

You taxi toward the FBO, rolling easy, breathing out the adrenaline. That was a crosswind landing that required real skill—and you delivered it. The FBO line guy meets you with chocks and a grin.

"Nice crosswind landing," he calls over the wind noise. "We've had three guys go around today."

You kill the engines and feel the sudden quiet. "Bet they all came back," you say.

"Two of them went to Eagle. You're the third to actually stick it."

Rachel unbuckles and leans forward. "I'm impressed," she says, and she means it.


The drive to Aspen is one hour and forty-five minutes, straight south down Highway 82 through Glenwood Canyon. The rental car is clean and quiet, and you settle in for the drive. The mountains slip away to the east and west as you descend. The canyon walls close in around you, red rock and green trees, the Colorado River running parallel to the road.

Halfway through the canyon, about 30 minutes into the drive, the weather catches up to you.

A thunderstorm drops on Glenwood Canyon without warning. Hail—marble-sized, loud on the rental car roof like ball bearings. The visibility drops to 200 yards. The canyon walls disappear into cloud. You ease off the gas and turn on the headlights. Other cars are doing the same, hazards blinking, brake lights bright in the gray.

Rachel is gripping the door handle. "This is bad."

"This is why we landed at Rifle," you say quietly.

The hail eases after five minutes. The visibility improves. The gray starts to break and you can see canyon walls again, wet and shining. The storm passes as quickly as it came.

"Was that the valley you were considering flying through?" Rachel asks.

You don't answer. You don't need to. She knows.

You arrive at Aspen at 1:15 PM. Ben is at the venue, arranging chairs and place settings, his wedding planner pointing at various sightlines. When he sees you, his face breaks into a smile. "You made it! I wasn't sure you would—the weather looked serious."

"It was," you say. "We made the right call landing at Rifle and driving."

"Glad you did," Ben says. "Really glad."


<div class="debrief">
<strong>DEBRIEF: A Solid Outcome</strong>

This is a solid outcome from a challenging situation. Your initial decision to deviate north toward Eagle County was sound—you read the weather, saw the building line along the Divide, and chose the path with lighter conditions. When the wall of weather between Eagle and Aspen proved impassable, your decision to continue to Rifle was reasonable. Rifle is closer to Aspen by road than Eagle is, and the airport is suitable for a challenging crosswind landing.

The crosswind landing at Rifle required confidence and skill but was appropriate for the environment. The runway is 7,000 feet long and 100 feet wide—far larger than what's needed for a 182. The terrain is flat. The airport is designed to handle significant wind. Your crosswind landing, executed cleanly, was exactly what the situation called for.

The decision NOT to attempt the Roaring Fork Valley—to see the narrowing valley, lowering ceiling, and gray sky to the south, and to choose the safe option instead—was critical. As the drive through Glenwood Canyon demonstrated, that valley contained worse weather than you could see from 10,500 feet.

<strong>Key Strength:</strong> You knew your crosswind skills and trusted them when the alternative was a mountain valley in deteriorating weather. A challenging landing at a safe airport beats a smooth approach into a narrowing box canyon. Every time.

<strong>Key Takeaway:</strong> The demonstrated crosswind component in your aircraft's POH (12.3 knots for the Cessna 182) is not your personal limit—it's a certification test condition, conducted under ideal circumstances with the most careful of pilots. A 500-1000 hour pilot who practices crosswind landings regularly can handle crosswinds beyond the demonstrated value, especially on a 7,000-foot runway with flat terrain and a large safety margin. Don't let the wind chase you into a valley. Don't underestimate your own skill.

</div>


<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
  _step
<</for>>

