<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: B2b-RoaringFork [scenario branch-b]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continuing into the Roaring Fork Valley"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<run crossfadeEngine("engine-smooth", "engine-rough", 3000)>><</if>>

"Rifle tower, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, we're going to continue south toward Aspen. Request descent into the Roaring Fork Valley."

A pause. Then: "Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, roger. Descend and maintain niner thousand. You've got traffic, a Regional going to Aspen. Keep the speed up."

You bank left, toward the south, away from Rifle. Rachel looks at you with a question in her eyes, but she doesn't ask it. She just nods and keeps watching the weather.

You descend to 8,500 feet and enter the Roaring Fork Valley from the northwest, coming down off the high plains and into the river drainage. The valley is three miles wide here, terrain rising to 10,000 and above on both sides. The ceiling is scattered at 9,500 feet. VFR, technically. Legal. But barely.

The first ten miles are fine. River below, Highway 82 snaking alongside it, small towns with funny names—Glenwood Springs, Carbondale. The valley is wide, the terrain is visible, the weather ahead is broken clouds. Aspen is 25 miles away. You've got fuel, you've got altitude, and you've got time.

Then the valley narrows.

It happens gradually at first, then more noticeably. The walls steepen. The ridgelines above the valley floor climb to 11,000, then 11,500. Your altitude is 8,500. Your terrain clearance is 2,500 feet, then 2,000. The ceiling drops—broken at 9,000, then broken at 8,700, then broken at 8,500. You're at your altitude. The clouds are right here with you.

Rain starts. Not heavy. Not severe. Just rain, steady, reducing the visibility. Ten miles becomes five. Five becomes four. You can still see the road, the river, but the valley ahead is gray. It's just gray. You can't see more than two miles into it.

The town of Carbondale passes below—the larger town, the last real town before Aspen. You look at your watch. Aspen is 15 miles away.

Rachel has been quiet, watching the weather build. Now she speaks: "Mike, what are we doing?"

"We're going down the valley."

"The ceiling is at our altitude."

"We've got four miles of visibility."

"And the valley is getting narrower."

She's right. She's absolutely right. The walls are tighter now, terrain on both sides at 10,000 and above, and your altitude is 8,500. That's 1,500 feet of vertical room. The valley is two miles wide at the widest points you can see ahead, narrowing to one mile in places. The ceiling is still at 8,500. Your margin is getting thin.

You have two options, and you need to choose now, while the valley is still wide enough at Carbondale:

<<link "Execute a 180 right now and get back to Rifle—the valley is closing." "B2b-TurnBackRifle">>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reversed course, 180 in the valley"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "Continue south toward Aspen—you can still see the road, visibility is four miles, you're almost there." "B2b-PressAspen">>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Pressed into deteriorating conditions"])>>
<<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 2>>
<</link>>

:: B2b-TurnBackRifle [scenario branch-b ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<run crossfadeEngine("engine-rough", "engine-smooth", 3000)>><<audio "touchdown" play>><</if>>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["180 in the Roaring Fork Valley, turned back to Rifle")))>>

"Rifle tower, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot. We're going to reverse course. Request left turn, descend Rifle."

"Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, Rifle, approved left turn. Descend and maintain nine thousand. Welcome back."

You bank left, firmly, into a standard-rate 180-degree turn. The valley is wide enough at Carbondale—two miles across, maybe a bit more. The 182's turning radius at this speed is about 1,200 feet in calm air. You've got plenty of room.

As the nose comes around toward the north, the ceiling seems to lift. The gray ahead becomes a little less dark. The valley widens as you turn. Within five minutes, the ceiling lifts to 9,000. Visibility improves to six miles, then eight. The valley widens to three miles across. The rain eases.

You've flown out of the worst of it just by turning around.

Twenty minutes later, Rifle appears ahead. The FBO is visible, the runway clear, the windsock still standing straight out but less threatening now. You descend for approach and call the tower. "Rifle tower, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, inbound for landing."

"Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, Rifle. Wind two-seven-zero at one-eight, gusting two-four. Runway two-six is the active. Cleared to land."

The wind has eased slightly—that makes sense, the afternoon cooling a bit after the rain. One-eight sustained, gusting 24. You crab 20 degrees into the wind on final. At 50 feet, you transition to crab and kick. Right main, left main, nosewheel. The landing is firm but clean. You taxi in.

Rachel watched the valley closing behind you through the rear window as you turned. "That was getting bad," she says quietly.

"It was."

"I'm glad you turned around."

"So am I."


You secure the 182 and catch the 2:00 PM shuttle to Aspen. The drive through Glenwood Canyon is beautiful—the rain has freshened everything, and the canyon walls are bright with moisture. You arrive at the venue at 2:15 PM.

Ben is arranging centerpieces when he sees you. His face lights up. "You made it! I was starting to worry. I heard the weather was getting tight."

"It was getting tight," you say. "We made a call to go back to Rifle and drive."

"Smart call," Ben says. "Really smart. Rachel, did he explain what that meant?"

"He explained it very clearly," Rachel says, with a small smile. "Every mile into a narrowing valley is a mile you have to fly back out."


<div class="debrief">
<strong>DEBRIEF: The Right Decision at the Right Time</strong>

The 180-degree turn in the Roaring Fork Valley was the correct decision—and critically, it was made at the right time. Carbondale is the last point where the valley is wide enough for a safe standard-rate turn in a 182. Five miles further south, the valley narrows to the point where a 180-degree turn becomes genuinely risky. The Cessna 182's turning radius at this speed and altitude would be right at the edge of the valley walls.

Your decision to attempt the valley was the error—the weather signs were clear from Glenwood Springs. Lowering ceiling, narrowing valley, rain. The data was there. But the recovery was excellent. Key lesson: In mountain valley flying, the 180 is the most important maneuver—not for its difficulty, but for the difficulty of the *decision* to use it. Every experienced mountain pilot has a story about the moment they turned around. Most of them are alive to tell it.

<strong>Key Takeaway:</strong> Your turnaround point should be the widest part of the valley that still offers acceptable conditions, not the narrowest. If you're going to turn around—and you should have turned around at Glenwood Springs—do it when the valley is wide and your options are still open. Train yourself to see deterioration one step before it forces your hand. The valley always looks worse from inside than from above. Every mile you fly into a narrowing valley is a mile you have to fly back out, and at some point, there's no room for the turn anymore.

</div>


