:: B2b-PressAspen [scenario branch-b ending]
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-rough" stop>><</if>>
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continued into severely deteriorating conditions"])>>

"Rifle tower, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, continuing south toward Aspen."

"Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, Rifle, roger. Contact Denver. Descend and maintain eight thousand."

You continue south into the narrowing valley.

Visibility drops to two miles. Then one and a half. The ceiling is at your altitude—8,500 feet—and dropping. The terrain on both sides of the valley is at 10,000 feet and above. Your vertical clearance is zero. You are flying at terrain altitude in a narrowing valley with one and a half miles of visibility.

The rain is steady. The clouds are gray and thick. Ahead, the valley curves left and you drift right without quite realizing it until the G1000's terrain display colors the right side of the screen orange. Warning terrain. You're approaching the ridge.

Rachel's voice is sharp: "Mike."

You see it—trees on a ridge, maybe 500 feet away, high enough that you're looking at them rather than down at them. You bank hard left. The stall horn chirps—a warning that your angle of attack is aggressive. You lower the nose, add power, and level the wings.

Altimeter: 8,100 feet. Terrain beneath you: 8,050 feet.

You are fifty feet above a ridge in a thunderstorm.

The valley curves left ahead, and you follow it because there's no other choice. The rain is so heavy you can't see more than a few hundred yards. The synthetic vision display on the G1000 is coloring most of the screen red and orange—terrain, terrain all around.

Then, for just a moment, the clouds break. Through a tear in the overcast, you see it: Aspen's runway. Runway 33. Two miles ahead. You dive for it.

The approach is steep, too steep, and you're going too fast. You're not aligned with the runway. You're aligned with the terrain, trying to get down and below the clouds before they close back in. Your descent rate is 1,800 feet per minute. You are flying a powerdown dive toward a runway in a thunderstorm.

The runway grows larger. You're committed now. There's no go-around from this approach, not with a ridge 50 feet behind you. There's only forward.

Wheels touch on runway 33. You're doing 75 knots. Your landing gear compresses. You're rolling. The rain is hammering the windscreen. You fly the airplane off the runway at taxi speed, the prop feathering as you slow, and roll left toward the ramp.

The tower comes up, and the controller's voice is professional but strained: "November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, welcome to Aspen. Contact ground when able. And sir... I'd suggest you contact the FSDO when you get a chance."

The FSDO. Federal Safety Reporting.

You are alive. The airplane is safe on the ground. Rachel is crying, her hands shaking. You find a ramp spot and shut down the engines. Your shirt is soaked with sweat. Your hands are shaking. You saved this outcome through luck and a G1000 with synthetic vision. Without synthetic vision, without that break in the clouds, this is an accident report. This is a fatality.


<div class="debrief">
<strong>DEBRIEF: Luck and Synthetic Vision</strong>

This outcome is survivable only through luck and technology. You penetrated a line of thunderstorms over mountainous terrain after ATC explicitly recommended against it. The "gap" you thought you saw from Rifle was a radar gradient showing rain intensity, not clear air. You entered IMC at 13,500 feet with terrain rising above you on both sides. The downdraft pushed you below the ridgelines. You descended below VFR minimums—well below—in a valley you couldn't see.

A pilot without synthetic vision in this situation is fatally disoriented. The terrain is invisible. The way out is invisible. The downdraft is pushing you lower. At 8,100 feet with terrain at 8,050, you have no margin for error and no ability to recover if you don't see the ridge. Most 182s don't have synthetic vision. Most outcomes from this situation don't include a landing.

The tower's reference to the FSDO is real. This kind of arrival generates enforcement action. A controller observed an approach to Aspen that no reasonable pilot would have planned. Your license, your standing, your ability to fly will be questioned. But the regulatory consequences are the least of the problems.

You were 50 feet from a ridge. Trees at your altitude. Stall horn in the flare at 8,100 feet with 8,050 feet of granite beneath you. The synthetic vision gave you a chance. The break in the clouds gave you a runway. Those are miracles, not pilot technique.

<strong>Key Lesson:</strong> Fifteen miles to go is not a reason to continue—it's a measurement of how close you were to turning around when you should have. The 180 at Carbondale would have put you at Rifle with time, fuel, reputation, and peace of mind intact.

<strong>Key Takeaway:</strong> Scud running in mountain valleys kills experienced pilots. The 12,000-hour ATP-rated captain dies the same way the 500-hour private pilot does: pressed low in a valley with rising terrain, lowering ceiling, and no way out. It is not a matter of experience or skill. It is a matter of physics and geography. The valley rises. The ceiling drops. The margin disappears. And then there is no saving yourself.

</div>


