:: B3-TrySouth [scenario branch-b]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Attempting to penetrate the weather wall south"])>>
<<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<run crossfadeEngine("engine-smooth", "engine-rough", 3000)>><<audio "wind-turbulence" play>><</if>>

From overhead Eagle County, you turn south. The wall of weather between you and Aspen is visible, dark and defined, but you think you see something the radar might have missed: a lighter area between two cells, maybe five miles wide, somewhere in the vicinity of Vail. It's subtle. It's a visual impression. It's hope.

You key the mic. "Denver Center, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot. We're going to try to go south through that gap near Vail."

A pause. Then: "Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, I'm painting moderate to heavy returns in that area. The gap you might be seeing is painting as light returns—that could be rain, not clear air. I'd recommend against it. Multiple aircraft have diverted. Say your intentions."

The controller is telling you what the radar shows. The controller is recommending against it. The data is there. The professional advice is there.

You're at the edge. The first wisps of precipitation are streaking across the windshield. The turbulence is sharpening. You have maybe thirty seconds before you're committed.

Rachel is watching you. "What did the controller say?"

<<link "Abort — turn back to Eagle NOW. The radar says it's not a gap. Trust the radar." "B3a-RetreatEagle">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Aborted, retreating to Eagle"])>><</link>>
<<link "Push through — you're already here, the lighter area is right ahead, better to go through than turn in turbulence." "B3b-PressThrough">><<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 2>><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Pressed into the weather wall"])>><</link>>

:: B3b-PressThrough [scenario branch-b ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["In the thunderstorm over the mountains"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "wind-turbulence" volume 0.8 play>><</if>>

You push south.

The turbulence hits at the edge of the first cell. Moderate at first, then sharp jolts that rattle the yoke and shake your teeth. The 182 is a stable airplane, but this is not stable air. This is convective energy — rising and falling columns of air, wind shear, the chaos of thunderstorm circulation.

Rain. The windscreen becomes a water curtain. The visibility drops to half a mile. You're in cloud now, solid cloud. You can't see the wing tips. You're on instruments, but your scan is broken — part of you is trying to look out the windscreen through the rain, part of you is trying to read the G1000, part of you is trying to understand where the ground is.

The gap you were seeing from the north resolves into what it actually was — not clear air, but a gradient between moderate rain and heavy rain. A variation in reflectivity that looks like a gap from 38 miles away, but up close is just less-intense precipitation. You're not in a gap. You're in the weather.

A lightning flash fills the cockpit. Simultaneous with thunder — close, very close. The airplane lurches. A bolt passed near you, close enough that the electromagnetic pulse rattled something electrical. Your heart rate spikes.

Rachel's breathing is rapid. "Mike, get out of this!"

"Working on it," you say, but your voice sounds calm in a way that feels disconnected from your body.

The altimeter unwinds through 12,500. The G1000's synthetic vision display is solid red — terrain. Ridgelines at 12,000, 12,500, 13,000 on both sides. You are in a thunderstorm over a mountain range, descending, unable to climb. A downdraft has you at minus 500 feet per minute despite full power.

You declare MAYDAY. "Denver Center, Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot declaring MAYDAY. Thunderstorm over terrain, unable to maintain altitude, requesting emergency vectors."

"Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, understood. Turn heading north-northwest. The Eagle River valley is to your north."

The altimeter unwinds through 11,800. The synthetic vision shows a narrow slot opening to your left — the valley running toward Minturn, terrain dropping to 8,000 in that direction. It's your only way out.

You bank hard left, toward the valley, flying on instruments with the G1000's terrain display as your only reference. The altimeter shows 11,600, 11,400, 11,200. Descending, but the valley is opening up. The synthetic vision starts showing clear air below you.

At 10,200 feet, you break out of the cloud. Below you is I-70, the valley opening wide, VFR conditions. The weather wall is behind you. You are alive. Barely.

You land at Eagle County thirty minutes later, having aged ten years. The tower controller's voice is professionally flat: "Four-Seven-Two Golf Foxtrot, welcome back. Glad to have you on the ground."

<div class="debrief">
<strong>DEBRIEF — Thunderstorm Penetration Over Mountains</strong>

<strong>What happened:</strong> After deviating north to Eagle and finding the route to Aspen blocked, you attempted to penetrate the weather wall to the south. ATC explicitly recommended against it, providing radar data showing moderate to heavy returns. You entered the weather, encountered severe turbulence and a downdraft that pushed you below the ridgelines, declared MAYDAY, and escaped through a narrow valley slot using synthetic vision. You survived through luck and technology.

<strong>ADM analysis:</strong> This outcome required overriding professional radar analysis with a visual impression from 38 miles away. The "gap" was a reflectivity gradient, not clear air. A pilot without synthetic vision in this situation does not survive — the terrain is invisible, the escape route is invisible, and the downdraft is still pushing lower.

<strong>Hazardous attitudes present:</strong> Invulnerability ("I can see the gap"), macho ("I can fly through this"), and a fatal overconfidence in visual assessment over radar data. ATC gave you the information. You chose to disbelieve it.

<strong>What good judgment looks like here:</strong> Landing at Eagle. The weather between Eagle and Aspen was a wall. No gap, no corridor, no route was safe. The shuttle to Aspen takes 90 minutes. The decision to penetrate a line of thunderstorms over mountainous terrain is never defensible.

<strong>Key takeaway:</strong> When ATC says "I'd recommend against it" and "multiple aircraft have diverted," they are not making conversation. They are giving you information that, if you ignore it, makes you the subject of an accident report. The radar sees what your eyes cannot. Trust the radar.
</div>

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
