:: C-ContactFSS [scenario branch-c]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Called Flight Service for updated weather"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "radio-squelch" play>><</if>>

You key the mic: "Denver Radio, November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot on one-two-two-point-two."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, Denver Radio, go ahead."

You request an update on the route from your current position—about 30 miles west of KBJC, approaching the Divide—to Aspen. You mention the build-ups you're seeing, the Baron's PIREP from 40 minutes ago.

Flight Service gives you a mixed picture. The information is ambiguous and conflicting.

"We've got an AIRMET Sierra for mountain obscuration along the Continental Divide above one-two thousand. AIRMET Tango for moderate turbulence below one-five thousand. A Convective SIGMET is possible within the hour for the area from Red Table to Glenwood Springs—possible, not yet issued. Current Aspen: VFR, scattered at nine thousand AGL, winds two-one-zero at one-two. Eagle County is VFR, winds two-seven-zero at one-niner gusting two-eight. Rifle is reporting winds two-seven-zero at two-two gusting three-six."

"Copy. Any recent PIREPs?"

"We've got mixed reports. A Beech Baron reported moderate turbulence at Red Table about forty minutes ago and continued to Aspen. An SR22 turned back from the same area about twenty minutes ago reporting rapid build-ups and lowering ceilings."

So: one pilot made it. Another turned back. AIRMETs issued. Convective SIGMET possible but not yet. Aspen is fine. Eagle is windy. Rifle is very windy. The information does not give you a clear answer.

Rachel has been listening on her headset. "So... is it safe?"

The honest answer: you don't know. The information is genuinely ambiguous. Experienced pilots could reasonably disagree.

<<link "Continue on course with heightened awareness—Aspen is VFR, the Baron made it, and the SIGMET isn't issued yet. You'll stay alert and be ready to deviate." "C1-ContinueCautious">><<set $badchoices += 1>><</link>>

<<link "Turn back to KBJC—the Cirrus turned back, the AIRMETs are active, and a convective SIGMET is imminent. The trend is deteriorating." "C2-TurnBackKBJC">><</link>>

<<link "Request deviation to Eagle County through Center—it's the closest airport with a flyable route, and you can reassess from there." "C3-DivertEagle">><</link>>

:: C1-ContinueCautious [scenario branch-c]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continued cautiously toward Red Table"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" stop>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-rough" play>><</if>>

You continue on course. You're more alert now, scanning the build-ups ahead, watching the G1000 for any indication of weather. You tell yourself you'll turn at the first sign of real trouble.

Five minutes later—you spent three minutes on the radio with Flight Service, and you're now closer to the Divide—the convective SIGMET drops. Denver Center relays it: "Convective SIGMET three-seven Charlie, area of thunderstorms from Red Table VOR to Glenwood Springs VOR, tops above flight level three-five-zero, moving northeast at two-five knots. All aircraft avoid the area."

The cells that were "developing" at the opening are now a line of thunderstorms. And you're ten miles closer to them than you were five minutes ago.

The turbulence starts. Moderate chop, rain streaks on the windshield. Rachel grabs the armrest. Ahead, the gap between two cells is visible—maybe five miles wide. But the convective SIGMET says "avoid the area." You're in the area.

<<link "Execute immediate 180—the SIGMET just confirmed what the Cirrus pilot already knew. Get out now." "C1a-Turn180East">><</link>>

<<link "Push for the gap—you can see the other side, you're almost through." "C1b-PushGap">><<set $badchoices += 2>><</link>>

:: C1a-Turn180East [scenario branch-c ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["180 turn after SIGMET, heading east"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-rough" stop>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "touchdown" play>><</if>>

You execute the 180. Sharp, immediate, no hesitation. "Denver Center, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, executing a one-eighty. Unable to continue westbound."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger. Cleared through the Bravo at one-four thousand five hundred. KBJC is five-zero miles east, reporting VFR, winds two-eight-zero at one-two."

The air smooths within two miles of the turn. The build-ups recede behind you. Ahead: the Front Range, the plains, the safety of flat terrain and clear air.

You land at KBJC at 10:15 AM. The rental car counter is open. You're on I-70 by 10:45.

The drive to Aspen: four hours. Through the Eisenhower Tunnel, over Vail Pass where the thunderstorms are now visible to the south, massive and black, with lightning visible in broad daylight. Rain hammers the car.

Rachel navigates from the passenger seat. At one point she says: "That Flight Service call probably saved us."

"Maybe. The Cirrus pilot who turned back saved us too. We just had to listen."

You arrive in Aspen at 3:00 PM. Not in time for setup. In time for the dinner. Ben saves you a seat.

<div class="debrief">
<strong>What happened:</strong>
You gathered information, interpreted it conservatively, continued anyway, but then acted decisively when the convective SIGMET confirmed the deteriorating trend. The 180-degree turn in the middle of the flight—after you'd already committed to going forward—showed good airmanship and judgment recovery.

<strong>ADM analysis:</strong>
The initial decision to continue was optimism bias in action: "Aspen is VFR" and "the Baron made it" weighted more heavily than "the Cirrus turned back" and "SIGMET possible." When the SIGMET became fact, the data was no longer ambiguous. You acted on that. The critical moment was not the decision to continue—it was your ability to reverse that decision the instant the information changed.

<strong>Hazardous attitudes:</strong>
You resisted "Get-there-itis" long enough to listen to the data. That's the real win here. The temptation to push through the gap was real. You didn't.

<strong>What good judgment looks like:</strong>
Good judgment is not always saying "no." Sometimes it's saying "yes, but I'll stay alert, and if the picture changes, I'll change my decision too." You did that. You listened. You acted.

<strong>Key takeaway:</strong>
A convective SIGMET is not a suggestion. It's an "evacuate this airspace now" instruction from the aviation weather system. Information gathering (calling Flight Service) was smart. Continuing cautiously was a judgment call. But when the ambiguous picture became a concrete SIGMET, you did what the data said. That's professionalism.

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
<<if _i > 0>><br/><</if>>
_step
<</for>>

