:: C1b-PushGap [scenario branch-c ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Pushed into the convective SIGMET area"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine" stop>><</if>>

You push toward the gap. The convective SIGMET is a minute old. You're already here. The gap is visible. Five minutes to clear air on the other side.

The downdraft hits two miles into the gap. VSI: −2,000 feet per minute. Full power, pitched up, going down anyway. 14,000... 13,200... 12,500. The gap closes—the cells merge around you. IMC. Severe turbulence. G1000 synthetic vision: terrain everywhere, at and above your altitude.

You declare MAYDAY. Center vectors you north—heading 350, toward the Eagle River valley. Four minutes of blind instrument flying in severe turbulence, hands shaking on the yoke. Rachel hasn't made a sound. You're at 11,200 feet with 12,000-foot ridges on both sides when the rain lightens. At 10,800 you break out. The valley is below you. Eagle County 14 miles north. You land there with adrenaline still hammering.

Rachel, after the prop stops: "You flew into a thunderstorm."

It wasn't a question.

<div class="debrief">
<strong>What happened:</strong>
You had a convective SIGMET telling you to avoid the area. You saw a visible gap between cells and believed you could thread it. The gap closed. The downdraft overpowered the aircraft. You declared MAYDAY and found the Eagle River valley by instrument flying and luck. You landed safely, but that landing was the result of ATC help and survival, not proficiency.

<strong>ADM analysis:</strong>
You had all the information you needed: Flight Service briefing, active AIRMETs, a convective SIGMET issued minutes before you entered the area, and a Cirrus pilot who'd already turned back. You flew into the area anyway. The logic was: "I can see the other side." The physics of thunderstorms don't care about what you can see. Mature thunderstorm downdrafts routinely exceed 3,000 feet per minute. A Cessna 182 at high altitude produces maybe 500 feet per minute of climb. In that downdraft, you were a passenger, not a pilot. The fact that you survived doesn't mean the decision was sound—it means you got lucky.

<strong>Hazardous attitudes:</strong>
Invulnerability: "I'm a better pilot than that SR22 guy who turned back." Macho: "I can thread the gap." Get-there-itis: "We're almost through." All three worked together to put you in a SIGMET area.

<strong>What good judgment looks like:</strong>
A convective SIGMET means "this area contains severe weather that could exceed the performance of your aircraft." Full stop. No gap is visible enough to override it. Good judgment means trusting the system—Flight Service, the SIGMET, the Cirrus pilot's experience—more than your own eyeballs.

<strong>Key takeaway:</strong>
You called Flight Service. You got the information. And then you ignored it. The information has no value if you don't act on it. Gathering data and then overriding it with optimism is worse than not gathering it at all—it gives you a false sense of having made an informed decision.

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
<<if _i > 0>><br/><</if>>
_step
<</for>>

<<link "Return to Start">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: C2-TurnBackKBJC [scenario branch-c]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Turning back based on Flight Service briefing"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "radio-squelch" play>><</if>>

You make the call. "Denver Center, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, we're heading back to Broomfield. The briefing doesn't look good enough to continue."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger. Turn right heading one-one-zero, cleared through the Denver Class Bravo."

The air is smooth heading east. The Front Range is golden in the morning light. Behind you, the wall over the Divide is growing.

Rachel pulls off her headset. "The Baron pilot made it through. That SR22 that turned around—maybe he was just being cautious."

"Maybe."

"We have four hours of fuel. Aspen is reporting VFR. And you're a better pilot than whoever was flying that Cirrus."

She's not being reckless—she's being logical, from a non-pilot's perspective. The Baron made it. Aspen is clear. Why can't you?

"Rachel, the trend is wrong. The AIRMETs, the possible SIGMET, the Cirrus turning back—it's all pointing the same direction."

"I trust you. I just... the rehearsal dinner."

This is the test. She's not angry. She's disappointed. And she's making arguments that sound reasonable to a non-pilot.

<<link "Stay committed to the turn-back. You made the decision. Stick with it." "C2a-StayCommitted">><</link>>

<<link "Rachel's argument makes you reconsider—maybe you're being too cautious. Reverse the 180 and head back west." "C2b-Reverse180">><<set $badchoices += 2>><</link>>

:: C2a-StayCommitted [scenario branch-c ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Stayed committed to turn-back, driving to Aspen"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine" stop>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "touchdown" play>><</if>>

You don't answer immediately. You fly.

After a minute: "I hear you. And you're not wrong that Aspen is VFR right now. But 'right now' is the problem. The weather is deteriorating, not improving. The Cirrus that turned back was twenty minutes ahead of us—he saw what it's becoming. The Baron was forty minutes ago—that was a different sky."

Rachel is quiet for a long moment. Then: "OK."

You land at KBJC at 9:50 AM. Rachel handles the rental car while you tie down the Skylane. The drive to Aspen: four hours on I-70. Through the Eisenhower Tunnel, the road climbs into the mountains you just decided not to fly over. At Vail Pass, the thunderstorms are visible to the south—massive, dark, with lightning visible in broad daylight. Rain hammers the car over Independence Pass.

Rachel sees the storms. "Those are where we would have been?"

"Yeah."

She doesn't mention the rehearsal dinner again.

You arrive at 2:30 PM. Help with setup. Rachel tells Ben: "Mike made the right call." She says it simply, like it's a fact, and you realize that the conversation in the airplane wasn't doubt—it was processing.

<div class="debrief">
<strong>What happened:</strong>
You gathered information, made a conservative decision to turn back, and then withstood social pressure from your passenger to reverse that decision. You explained your reasoning clearly and committed to it. The weather visible on the drive confirmed your judgment.

<strong>ADM analysis:</strong>
This is the core test of aeronautical decision-making under pressure. You made a sound decision based on the trend data (AIRMETs active, SIGMET possible, Cirrus turned back). Rachel's arguments were logically sound from a non-pilot perspective: the Baron made it, Aspen is VFR, you have fuel. But they missed the critical point: weather changes by the minute. The sky the Baron saw 40 minutes ago is not the sky you're looking at now. You understood that. More importantly, you stuck with it.

<strong>Hazardous attitudes:</strong>
You resisted all of them: Invulnerability (you didn't overestimate your ability to handle the weather), Macho (you didn't let pride force you to prove something), Get-there-itis (you accepted the cost of the drive). The temptation to reverse the turn-back to please a passenger is subtle and human. You didn't fall for it.

<strong>What good judgment looks like:</strong>
Good judgment is the ability to make a decision based on incomplete information, and then to stick with it even when someone you care about is disappointed by it. Rachel trusted you—that's what made this hard. And you honored that trust by not using her disappointment as an excuse to unmake a sound decision.

<strong>Key takeaway:</strong>
Social pressure is the most underrated hazard in general aviation. The NTSB accident database is full of cases where the pilot made a good initial decision and reversed it because of passenger, family, or professional pressure. Once you've made a safety decision, commit. Don't relitigate it at altitude. The pilot who turns back and sticks with it tells one story: "We drove." The pilot who turns back, reverses, and pushes into weather tells a different story—and sometimes it's told by the NTSB.

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
<<if _i > 0>><br/><</if>>
_step
<</for>>

<<link "Return to Start">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: C2b-Reverse180 [scenario branch-c]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reversed the 180, heading back west"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" stop>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-rough" play>><</if>>

"Maybe you're right. The Baron made it. Aspen is VFR. Let me take another look."

You turn back west. Rachel looks relieved. But as you approach the Divide again—five minutes later than your first approach—the picture has changed. The cells that were developing are now towering. The corridor you had near Red Table is gone.

The convective SIGMET drops as you're ten miles out: "Area of thunderstorms from Red Table to Glenwood Springs, tops above FL350."

You are heading directly into a SIGMET area that didn't exist—or wasn't issued—when you made this decision.

<<link "Stop. Turn around AGAIN. This was a mistake." "C2b-180Again">><</link>>

<<link "You're already here, you reversed the turn-back, you can't turn around twice—Rachel will think you're indecisive. Press on." "C2b-PressOnWeather">><<set $badchoices += 1>><</link>>

:: C2b-180Again [scenario branch-c ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["180 again—back east for good this time"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-rough" stop>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine-smooth" play>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "touchdown" play>><</if>>

You bank hard right. "Denver Center, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, I'm sorry—we're heading east. For good this time."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger. No need to apologize. Cleared through the Bravo. Good decision."

Rachel looks at you. She doesn't say anything about the reversal. She saw the wall of weather ahead. She knows.

You land at KBJC at 10:30 AM. The drive to Aspen is four hours. You arrive at 3:00 PM. You're quiet for most of the drive. At Copper Mountain, Rachel says: "I'm sorry I pushed."

"You didn't push. You asked a reasonable question."

"Still. I should have let you fly."

"You did let me fly. I just took the scenic route to the right answer."

<div class="debrief">
<strong>What happened:</strong>
You made the right decision (turn back), reversed it under social pressure (the most dangerous moment in the scenario), and then had the discipline to re-reverse when the weather confirmed your original instincts. The double-180 cost you time, fuel, and composure. It didn't cost you your life.

<strong>ADM analysis:</strong>
This path reveals the true hazard of social pressure: it can override your judgment so completely that you make decisions you know are wrong. When you turned west again, you weren't flying based on your judgment—you were flying based on Rachel's reasonable-sounding arguments. The moment the SIGMET dropped, you had data again, and you recognized it. The critical skill was not the ability to recognize the mistake—it was the courage to correct it, even after you'd already reversed course once.

<strong>Hazardous attitudes:</strong>
Concern with people-pleasing: "Rachel will think I'm indecisive if I turn around twice." That concern almost killed you both. The other pilot—and yourself—care far more about whether you land safely than whether your turns look decisive.

<strong>What good judgment looks like:</strong>
Good judgment includes the ability to recognize when you've made a mistake and correct it immediately, regardless of how it looks. Turning around twice is not a sign of indecision—it's a sign that you were willing to listen to information, and when that information contradicted your revised decision, you acted on the new data. That's professionalism.

<strong>Key takeaway:</strong>
If you find yourself heading back toward weather you already decided was unacceptable, ask yourself: "What changed?" If the answer is "my passenger made a compelling argument," nothing changed except your resolve. Turn around again. There is no embarrassment in being right twice. There is only relief that you're alive.

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
<<if _i > 0>><br/><</if>>
_step
<</for>>

<<link "Return to Start">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: C2b-PressOnWeather [scenario branch-c ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Pressed into SIGMET area after reversing safety decision"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine" stop>><</if>>

You don't turn around. You can't turn around twice—how would that look? Rachel would think you can't make a decision. You're the pilot in command. Make a choice and stick with it.

This is the most dangerous sentence in aviation: "I can't turn around now."

The weather swallows the airplane. Moderate turbulence becomes severe. Rain is a wall. IMC in seconds. The G1000 shows terrain rising on both sides. You're at 13,800 and descending in a downdraft you can't overcome.

You declare MAYDAY. Center tries to help. But you're deep in the weather now, in the mountains, below the ridgelines, in solid IMC. The controller's voice is the last professional voice you hear: "Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, turn right heading three-five-zero, climb and maintain—"

The radar track ends at 12,400 feet on the west face of a 13,200-foot ridge. The wreckage is found two days later by a search and rescue team.

<div class="debrief">
<strong>What happened:</strong>
You made a sound decision, reversed it for social reasons, recognized the mistake, and then chose appearance over survival. That choice killed you.

<strong>ADM analysis:</strong>
The chain of events was: (1) gathered good information from Flight Service, (2) correctly interpreted the deteriorating trend, (3) made a sound turn-back decision, (4) reversed it under social pressure from a passenger with non-pilot logic, (5) had convective SIGMET confirm that your original judgment was correct, (6) chose not to reverse again because of what it would look like to Rachel. The fatal error was not aeronautical—it was psychological. You prioritized how the decision looked over what the decision was. This is how experienced pilots die: not from ignorance, but from the belief that being decisive is more important than being alive.

<strong>Hazardous attitudes:</strong>
Macho: "I'm the pilot in command; I have to commit to a course of action." Concern with appearances: "Turning around twice would look bad." Resignation: "I've already reversed once; I can't reverse again." All three together created the fatal decision.

<strong>What good judgment looks like:</strong>
Good judgment would have recognized the SIGMET for what it was: confirmation that the original decision was correct. Good judgment would have said, "I was right the first time. I'm going back east." That decision would have been awkward. It would have required explaining to Rachel why you'd changed your mind again. It would have required a conversation about how weather doesn't care about how your decisions look. But you would have landed safely in an empty seat at dinner, not in a ridge.

<strong>Key takeaway:</strong>
Passengers don't make aeronautical decisions. You do. When you've decided to turn back, the discussion is over. The next conversation is about which rental car agency to use. If you find yourself in a second decision point about the same weather, remember the Cirrus pilot who turned back the first time. Remember that the information is telling you something. And remember that no dinner, no wedding, no passenger's disappointment is worth your life. The NTSB probable cause will read: "The pilot's decision to continue VFR flight into instrument meteorological conditions in mountainous terrain, after initially deciding to return to the departure airport. Contributing factors: social pressure from the passenger and the pilot's reversal of a sound aeronautical decision."

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
<<if _i > 0>><br/><</if>>
_step
<</for>>

<<link "Return to Start">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: C3-DivertEagle [scenario branch-c]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverting to Eagle County"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "radio-squelch" play>><</if>>

"Denver Center, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, requesting deviation to Eagle County."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, deviation approved. Proceed direct Eagle County VOR. Eagle ATIS information Bravo: winds two-seven-zero at one-niner gusting two-eight, scattered at one-two thousand, visibility one-zero plus."

You turn north. The flight to Eagle takes thirty-five minutes. The corridor along the Gore Range is cleaner—scattered build-ups but nothing like the wall to the south. You descend into the Eagle River valley and enter the pattern.

Eagle's winds: 270 at 19 gusting 28. Runway 07/25—a moderate crosswind. The pattern is bumpy—mechanical turbulence from the ridgelines—but manageable. On final, a gust rocks you. You correct. The PAPI shows on-glide. This is a mountain airport in the afternoon—it's demanding but flyable.

<<link "Commit to the landing at Eagle. The approach is stable, the crosswind is manageable, and Eagle is a 9,000-foot runway with full services. Land here." "C3a-LandEagle">><</link>>

<<link "You're stable on approach, but Rifle ATIS shows winds shifted to 250 at 15 gusting 22. That's only a 10-degree crosswind—much easier. And it's closer to Aspen by road. Overfly Eagle and continue to Rifle." "C3b-ContinueRifle">><</link>>

:: C3a-LandEagle [scenario branch-c ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed at Eagle County"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine" stop>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "touchdown" play>><</if>>

Standard landing at Eagle. Crosswind: firm aileron correction, crab and kick at the flare. The 9,000-foot runway absorbs any excess energy. You taxi to Signature.

It's 10:40 AM. The 11:00 shuttle to Aspen. You'll be there by 12:30.

Rachel at the shuttle stop: "Thank you for calling Flight Service."

"It didn't tell us anything definitive."

"No. But it gave you enough to make the decision. That's what information does, right? It doesn't decide for you. It lets you decide better."

She's exactly right. You make a note to tell her that over dinner.

<div class="debrief">
<strong>What happened:</strong>
You gathered information, interpreted it conservatively, diverted to the closest safe airport with ground transport, and landed without incident. The key skill was not flying—it was information processing and good resource management.

<strong>ADM analysis:</strong>
You weighted the trend over the snapshot. The ambiguous picture from Flight Service (AIRMETs active, SIGMET possible, Baron made it, Cirrus turned back, Aspen is VFR) tilted you toward caution. Rather than betting on a single positive indicator, you chose to land at a safe airport and reassess. This is the textbook application of conservative aeronautical decision-making in ambiguous conditions. The information didn't give you a clear "go," so you treated it as a "no-go" from that altitude and executed a diversion to known good conditions.

<strong>Hazardous attitudes:</strong>
You didn't exhibit any. You resisted invulnerability (didn't assume you could handle the weather better than the Cirrus), macho (didn't feel the need to prove anything), and get-there-itis (accepted the shuttle ride). The decision to divert was the opposite of all those attitudes—it was humility and respect for the system.

<strong>What good judgment looks like:</strong>
Good judgment is the ability to gather information, recognize when it doesn't give you a clear answer, and take action to resolve the ambiguity from a position of safety (10,000 feet with an airport directly below) rather than from a position of commitment (pushing toward weather you're not confident about). You did that.

<strong>Key takeaway:</strong>
Information gathering is only valuable if you act on what you learn. Calling Flight Service was smart. Diverting to Eagle was smarter. Neither was dramatic or heroic—which is exactly the point. The best mountain flying is the kind that doesn't generate stories. It generates safe landings and rental car rides.

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
<<if _i > 0>><br/><</if>>
_step
<</for>>

<<link "Return to Start">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: C3b-ContinueRifle [scenario branch-c ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Overflew Eagle, continued to Rifle"])>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "engine" stop>><</if>>
<<if $audioEnabled>><<audio "touchdown" play>><</if>>

You overfly Eagle and continue west. The flight to Rifle takes another thirty minutes. The valley is wide, the ride smooth. Rifle's winds have indeed improved—250 at 15 gusting 22. The landing is straightforward.

It's 11:30 AM. The drive to Aspen: an hour forty-five through Glenwood Canyon.

Rachel in the rental car: "We flew right over an airport."

"Rifle was closer to Aspen. Less driving."

"But we were RIGHT over Eagle. We could have been done."

She has a point. The extra thirty minutes of flying saved you maybe forty-five minutes of driving. But it cost fuel, it extended the flight, and it required you to fly further into the mountains with weather building. The math worked out this time. It doesn't always.

You arrive in Aspen at 1:15 PM. Plenty of time.

<div class="debrief">
<strong>What happened:</strong>
You made good decisions through most of the chain: called Flight Service, interpreted the ambiguous data conservatively, diverted toward Eagle. But then you overflew Eagle—a safe airport with full services and a 9,000-foot runway—to reach Rifle, 30 minutes further into the mountains, because it would save time on the ground drive.

<strong>ADM analysis:</strong>
This is the decision trap of optimization. The extra 30 minutes of flying saved maybe 45 minutes of ground driving. The math looks sound in smooth conditions, which is what you had. But the principle is wrong. You're making the air portion of the flight longer and more risky in order to make the ground portion slightly shorter. In mountain flying, that's backwards. The extra 30 minutes of fuel burn, the extended time aloft, the flying further from your safe-haven airport—all of that increases your exposure to the weather you already decided to divert around. This time, the valley was clear and the wind at Rifle was favorable. Next time, those conditions might not exist.

<strong>Hazardous attitudes:</strong>
Invulnerability (a subtle kind): "The weather didn't materialize, so the extra 30 minutes of flying was fine." That attitude creates habits. And habits are what kill pilots. You built the habit of overflying a safe airport.

<strong>What good judgment looks like:</strong>
Good judgment recognizes that the best airport in mountain flying is the one you're already over. Eagle to Aspen by shuttle takes 90 minutes. Rifle to Aspen by car takes 105 minutes. You spent 30 minutes of flying to save 15 minutes of driving. That's not a trade mountain pilots should make as a habit.

<strong>Key takeaway:</strong>
When you have a safe airport below you in mountain flying, land there. Not the next one, not the "better" one 30 miles further into the peaks. The one below you. The extra flying doesn't get you there faster on average; it just increases your exposure to weather you already diligently checked. This outcome is safe because the weather cooperated. But it's a decision born of optimization, not judgment.

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
<<if _i > 0>><br/><</if>>
_step
<</for>>

<<link "Return to Start">><<run Engine.restart()>><</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: D-ClimbHigher [scenario branch-d]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Climbing to 16,500 for better position"])>>

You key the mic: "Denver Center, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, requesting climb to one-six thousand five hundred."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, climb and maintain VFR at one-six thousand five hundred."

Rachel looks at you. "Higher? Isn't the weather up there?"

"The weather is at 14 to 15 thousand. At 16,500 we'll be above most of the bases and we can see the full picture."

The 182 climbs. It's slower up here — maybe 300 fpm at this density altitude. You reach behind the seat for the portable O2 system. FAR 91.211: above 14,000 MSL, required for the flight crew at all times. Above 15,000, passengers too after 30 minutes. You hand Rachel a cannula.

"What's this?"

"Oxygen. We need it at this altitude."

She puts it on without argument. Good.

At 16,500, the picture changes dramatically. From 14,500, the build-ups along the Divide looked like a wall. From 16,500, you can see OVER most of the bases. The towering cumulus punches well above you, but the cells aren't everywhere. From up here, you can see what you couldn't from below:

A navigable corridor to the north, along the Eagle River valley. The build-ups are concentrated over the Sawatch Range and the highest terrain. The corridor between your position and Eagle County VOR is relatively clear — scattered cumulus below you, no cells penetrating above your altitude.

The cells to the south and on your direct course are blocking hard — now you can see they're already towering, with anvils forming. Red Table is not passable.

The terrain clearance at 16,500 is substantial. The Continental Divide here is 12,000 to 13,000 feet. You've got 3,500 to 4,500 feet of terrain clearance — enough for comfortable passage even with turbulence.

To the west, past the worst of the cells, the Roaring Fork Valley and the terrain toward Aspen looks clearer — scattered clouds, no cells visible. The weather is concentrated over the Divide itself.

The tradeoffs are real: fuel burn is higher at this altitude, the portable O2 is limited — maybe two hours for two people, engine performance is reduced. But you can SEE. From 14,500, you were flying blind into uncertainty. From 16,500, you have options.

<<link "Navigate the corridor at 16,500 — use the altitude advantage to thread through the clearest area north of the worst cells" "D1-NavigateCorridor">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Navigating the corridor at 16,500 — threading north"])>><</link>>

<<link "Descend to Eagle County — the view from 16,500 confirmed the direct route is blocked. Use the information and land." "D2-DescendEagle">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Descending to Eagle County from altitude"])>><</link>>

<<link "Turn back east at altitude — the weather is serious, and you have the energy and visibility to exit while you can" "D3-TurnBackAltitude">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Turning back east from 16,500"])>><</link>>

:: D1-NavigateCorridor [scenario branch-d]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Identifying and threading the northern corridor"])>>

You pick your route. From 16,500, the corridor north of Red Table is clear — a band of sky between the cell line to the south and a thin overcast layer to the north. The corridor is maybe 15 miles wide. Below you, the terrain slides past: the Eagle River valley, the Gore Range, the peaks of the Tenmile Range. The air is smooth at this altitude — the turbulence is down at the cell boundaries, and you're above most of it.

The O2 cannula hisses softly. Rachel is looking out the window at the cells to the south — from up here, you can see the anvil tops spreading east, the dark bases, the rain shafts. It's beautiful and terrifying from a distance.

"Those are thunderstorms," she says.

"Those are why we're up here instead of down there."

Twenty minutes. You cross the Divide. The terrain drops away on the western slope — 13,000, 12,000, 10,000 feet. The Eagle River valley opens below you, wide and green. To the south, the weather over the Divide is a wall behind you. Ahead, to the southwest, the Roaring Fork Valley stretches toward Aspen. The ceiling over the valley is high — broken at 12,000, visibility good. Aspen is 30 miles ahead, and the weather report still says VFR.

But you can see something developing from the south. The weather over the Divide isn't staying on the Divide. It's moving northeast — the cells are drifting toward Aspen. Your view from 16,500 shows you the timeline clearly: maybe 30 to 40 minutes before the first cells reach the Aspen area. Enough time to get there, but not with a generous margin.

<<link "Descend toward Aspen now — 30 miles at 150 knots is 12 minutes. Tight, but doable before the weather arrives." "D1a-PushAspen">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Descending toward Aspen with weather timeline calculated"])>><</link>>

<<link "Descend toward Rifle instead — 25 miles to the west, further from the approaching weather. Safer margin." "D1b-DivertRifle">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverting to Rifle — wider weather margin"])>><</link>>

:: D1a-PushAspen [scenario branch-d ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landing at Aspen with weather right behind"])>>

You begin descending. Power back, 500 fpm down. At 14,000 you remove the O2 cannulas. The Roaring Fork Valley opens up below — Highway 82, the river, the town of Basalt. Aspen's runway is visible ahead, nestled in the valley.

Aspen tower: "November four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, Aspen Tower, runway three-three, winds two-two-zero at one-five, altimeter three-zero-zero-eight. Report a three-mile final."

You enter the pattern. The air is smooth in the valley — a gentle tailwind component on the base leg, turning to a crosswind on final. Textbook. You touch down on 33 and taxi to Atlantic Aviation. It's 10:45 AM.

Rachel takes off the cannula she'd been wearing and looks at it. "That was a lot of preparation for what ended up being a normal landing."

"The preparation is what made it normal."

She considers this. "Like rehearsing for a wedding that might rain?"

"Exactly like that."

You arrive at the venue at 11:30 AM. Ben is directing table placements. "You're early! How was the flight?"

"Interesting weather. We went over it."

"Over it? I thought the clouds were at like 15,000 feet."

"16,500."

He looks impressed. Rachel hangs her garment bag. Through the venue windows, you can see the first dark clouds approaching from the northeast. Twenty minutes later, it's raining in Aspen. Thirty minutes after that, there's thunder.

Your timing was right. Your margin was thin. But you had the information to know it was thin, and you made it work.

<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: The Optimal Outcome</strong>

This is the best possible decision chain in the entire scenario. You recognized the ambiguous weather picture, climbed for better situational awareness instead of pressing at 14,500 or turning back, and from altitude, correctly identified the navigable corridor. You crossed the Divide with adequate terrain clearance, descended to Aspen with accurate assessment of the weather timeline, and landed before the cells arrived.

The key insight: climbing to 16,500 — which seems more aggressive in every way — actually gave you more information, more options, and more safety margin than staying at 14,500. From 14,500, the weather looked like an impenetrable wall. From 16,500, you could see the gaps, the movement, the structure. You could see that the corridor existed. You could see that Aspen was reachable within the weather window.

<strong>Key Lesson: Altitude is Information</strong>

In mountain flying, climbing when the weather is ambiguous can give you a picture that lower altitudes cannot provide. The costs are real — fuel burn increases, your O2 supply is finite, engine performance degrades, density altitude limits your climb rate. These tradeoffs exist. They matter. And they're worth it because they buy you something that every mountain accident report shows pilots desperately needed: a complete picture of what's ahead before you commit to going there.

Other pilots at 14,500 feet right now are turning back or deviating or pushing into cells that look "maybe passable." You went up. From up there, you could see what they couldn't.

<strong>Principle: The Counterintuitive Decision</strong>

The harder choice — the one that costs fuel and requires O2 and feels like you're wasting performance — is often the safer one. Pilots tend to think of altitude as an escalation: "we're going higher, so we're being more aggressive." In reality, altitude in ambiguous mountain weather is a de-escalation. It's stepping back to see the whole board instead of playing the next move in fog. You didn't push higher to blast through the weather. You climbed higher to understand the weather. Then you flew through it because you understood it.

<strong>The Weather Didn't Change; Your Understanding Did</strong>

When you turned onto the Denver Vector at 14,500 feet, the weather was exactly where it is now. The cells over the Divide were already there. The corridor was already there. The timeline of the weather moving northeast was already in motion. The only thing that changed is that you got above it and could see it all at once.

This is the lesson that separates good mountain pilots from ones who push the weather until it kills them.
</div>

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<ul>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
<li>_step</li>
<</for>>
</ul>

