<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>
:: D1b-DivertRifle [scenario branch-d ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landing at Rifle with wider weather margin"])>>

You descend toward Rifle. The Colorado River valley opens up to the west — lower terrain, wider valleys, and the weather is clearly to your south and east. Rifle's ASOS has updated: winds 250 at 14 gusting 20. Better than earlier — the afternoon shift hasn't fully kicked in yet.

The approach to Rifle is uneventful. You touch down on Runway 26 with a light crosswind. Taxi to Atlantic Aviation. Shut down.

It's 11:00 AM. The drive to Aspen: one hour forty-five through Glenwood Canyon. You arrive at 12:45 PM. Plenty of time.

At the venue, Rachel says to Ben: "Your friend flew us over the Continental Divide at 16,500 feet."

Ben: "In a Cessna? Is that even possible?"

"Apparently, if you bring oxygen."

You set up chairs. The rehearsal dinner is relaxed. Around 4:00 PM, a thunderstorm rolls through Aspen — hard rain, hail, lightning. Everyone retreats inside. You watch it through the window and think about the corridor you flew through four hours earlier, now invisible behind a wall of rain.

<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: The Conservative Excellence</strong>

This is an excellent outcome. Your decision chain was sound throughout: climb for awareness, identify the corridor, cross the Divide at altitude with adequate terrain clearance, and then — rather than pressing for Aspen with weather approaching — you chose the conservative option and landed at Rifle with wider safety margins.

The decision to go to Rifle instead of Aspen shows mature risk assessment. You COULD have made Aspen — the weather window was open, you had the information, the approach was feasible. But you chose not to test the margins when a safe, closer option was available. That's not timidity. That's wisdom.

<strong>Key Lesson: Options Are Not Obligations</strong>

Having options is not the same as exercising them. You could see from 16,500 that Aspen was reachable — the corridor was clear, the descent path was good, the timeline worked. But you also saw the weather moving toward it. Choosing Rifle meant wider margins, lower pressure, and a short drive. The extra 105 minutes of driving bought you certainty instead of probability.

In aviation, certainty is worth more than it costs.

<strong>The Margins Matter More Than the Destination</strong>

If you'd pressed to Aspen and made it (and statistically, you would have), you'd land and think "great decision." If you'd pressed to Aspen and had a close call or missed the window, you'd think "why didn't I land at Rifle?" Both outcomes are possible. Landing at Rifle eliminates the second outcome entirely. It trades a tight victory for a comfortable one.

That trade is the definition of good judgment in mountain flying.

<strong>Principle: Overflying Safety</strong>

The hardest part of being a good pilot isn't being capable. It's being comfortable with good enough. Rifle's runway is 9,000 feet. The winds are manageable. The terrain is lower. The approach is straightforward. These are not the minimums. These are better than minimums, and they're right here. Taking them is not settling. It's flying the flight you have, not the one you imagined.
</div>

