:: D2-DescendEagle [scenario branch-d]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Confirming direct route blocked — descending to Eagle County"])>>

From 16,500, the picture is clear: the direct route is blocked, the corridor exists but requires continued mountain flying, and Eagle County is directly below you with a clear approach path. You've spent 10 minutes at altitude, burned extra fuel, and used O2 — but you've bought yourself the information to make a confident decision.

"Denver Center, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, descending to Eagle County."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, squawk VFR, frequency change approved."

You pull power and descend. At 12,000 you remove the O2 cannulas. The Eagle River valley rises to meet you. You enter the pattern at Eagle — winds 270 at 19 gusting 28. The crosswind is manageable on the 9,000-foot runway.

But on downwind, you notice something. The ASOS at Eagle just updated: winds shifting to 290 at 22 gusting 30. And from the pattern altitude, you can see a rotor cloud forming over the ridge to the west — mechanical turbulence from the strong westerly flow. The pattern is getting bumpy.

<<link "Land at Eagle now — you're in the pattern, the crosswind is manageable, and conditions are deteriorating. Get it done." "D2a-LandEagle">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landing at Eagle — conditions deteriorating"])>><</link>>

<<link "Abandon the approach, continue west to Rifle — wind might be better aligned, and Rifle is closer to Aspen by road." "D2b-ContinueToRifle">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Overflying Eagle, continuing to Rifle"])>><</link>>

:: D2a-LandEagle [scenario branch-d ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Successfully landed at Eagle County"])>>

You fly the approach. Gusts on final rock the 182 but the 9,000-foot runway is reassuring. You land with a crosswind correction, firm but on centerline. Taxi to Signature.

It's 10:30 AM. Shuttle to Aspen at 11:00. Arrive 12:30 PM.

At the shuttle stop, Rachel takes off the O2 cannula she'd forgotten in her pocket. "I didn't expect to need supplemental oxygen on a flight to a wedding."

"I didn't expect the weather to look like that either."

"But you had a plan."

"I had altitude. Same thing."

<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: Information Before Distance</strong>

This is a clean decision chain from start to finish. You recognized the ambiguous weather, climbed for better situational awareness, confirmed the situation from altitude, and landed at the nearest safe airport without hesitation. Every decision was made from a position of strength — altitude, fuel, information, and no pressure.

The climb to 16,500 cost about 10 minutes and some fuel but gave you certainty that would have been impossible from 14,500. From lower altitude, you might have pressed into the weather, agonized over the decision, or requested multiple vectors. From 16,500, the answer was obvious: the direct route was blocked, Eagle was below you, land.

<strong>Key Lesson: Clarity Over Guesswork</strong>

Sometimes the most valuable thing altitude gives you isn't terrain clearance — it's clarity. The decision to land at Eagle was easy from 16,500 because you could SEE that the alternatives were blocked. The cells were not just getting in your way; they were growing. The corridor existed but required pushing further into mountain flying in deteriorating conditions. Eagle was a 9,000-foot runway directly below you with a clean approach.

From 14,500, the same decision requires educated guesswork: Are the cells that bad? Is the corridor really there? Are they blocking the route or just looking threatening? How long do I have before this gets worse? You'd be flying on probability instead of observation.

<strong>The Cost of Information</strong>

The decision to land at Eagle also reveals something about the cost of information. You climbed 2,000 feet, which cost fuel, burned O2, and took time. A direct pilot pressed at 14,500 might have made Aspen on the first try with less fuel burned. But you didn't know whether the direct route was viable until you climbed and looked. The fuel you spent was the cost of confidence. That's a trade that pays for itself the moment you avoid a problem that a lower-altitude pilot would have walked into blind.

<strong>Principle: Airport Below You is Your Best Alternate</strong>

Eagle's 9,000-foot runway below you at 10,500 feet is the finest alternate you'll ever have. Close, known, visible, with a clear approach. The temptation to push on to a "better" airport (Aspen, further west) is a trap. The airport in front of you beats every airport you can only imagine.

This is especially true in mountain weather. Taking the good airport in front of you when conditions are deteriorating beats searching for the perfect airport while conditions worsen.
</div>

