:: D2b-ContinueToRifle [scenario branch-d ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Overflying Eagle, continuing to Rifle"])>>

You abandon the approach at Eagle and continue west. The flight to Rifle takes twenty-five minutes along the Eagle River valley. The ride is bumpy — mechanical turbulence from the strong westerlies. You descend to 10,500.

Rifle ASOS: winds 250 at 16 gusting 24. Better than earlier. The crosswind on 26 is moderate. You land without drama.

It's 11:15 AM. Drive to Aspen: one hour forty-five. Arrive 1:00 PM.

The FBO lineman at Rifle: "Busy day. You're the fourth diversion from over the Divide."

Rachel: "I guess climbing to 16,500 was the right call?"

"It told us what we needed to know."

"But we still ended up driving."

"Yeah. But we ended up driving from the closest safe airport to Aspen, in a calm airplane, with plenty of fuel and no emergencies. That's not the worst version of driving."

<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: Safety Preserved, Judgment Mixed</strong>

A safe outcome, but the decision-making shows a weak link. You made excellent decisions through most of the chain — climbing for situational awareness, identifying the blocked route, beginning the diversion. Overflying Eagle to reach Rifle was the suboptimal choice: it added 25 minutes of mountain flying in deteriorating conditions to save 45 minutes of driving. The savings worked out this time, but the principle is questionable in mountain weather.

When you're in the pattern at a safe mountain airport and conditions are deteriorating, the decision to land should be almost automatic. Continuing to search for a "better" airport introduces risk for a dubious gain.

<strong>Key Lesson: Don't Overfly Safety Chasing Convenience</strong>

Eagle's 9,000-foot runway was right there. The approach was clear. The crosswind was within limits. The winds were gusting but manageable. The only reason to skip it was a vague sense that Rifle might be "easier" or "better positioned" for the drive. Those are marginal gains. The cost of continuing was 25 more minutes of flight time in mechanical turbulence with deteriorating winds, over terrain that doesn't forgive mistakes.

You made it to Rifle without incident. That means the risk was worth it, by the outcome. But the outcome doesn't validate the decision. You rolled dice that could have come up differently.

<strong>The Risk Calculation You Didn't Make</strong>

What if the winds had shifted further north? What if the rotor got worse? What if you'd encountered unexpected icing or a downdraft? You were committing to 25 more minutes of exposed mountain flying to save a 45-minute drive. The math doesn't work when conditions are deteriorating.

The right way to think about Eagle: you were handed the best alternate you'd ever get — visible, close, adequate, with a clear approach. Taking it isn't settling. It's flying the flight in front of you instead of chasing the flight you imagined.

<strong>Principle: Conservative Decision-Making Doesn't Mean Timid</strong>

Landing at Eagle instead of pressing to Rifle wouldn't have been cautious flying. It would have been good flying. You had information from 16,500 that the weather was serious and growing. You had an adequate airport below you. You had deteriorating conditions and winds shifting. The decision to land was based on reading those facts. The decision to continue was based on preference.

In mountain weather, facts beat preference.
</div>

