:: D3-TurnBackAltitude [scenario branch-d]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Turning back east — weather too serious from 16,500"])>>

From 16,500, the picture is unambiguous: the weather over the Divide is established and growing. No route to Aspen is clean. You've seen enough.

"Denver Center, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, we're heading east. Returning to Broomfield."

"Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger. Cleared through the Bravo at one-six thousand five hundred. Descend at pilot's discretion."

The 182 turns east. From this altitude, the view is extraordinary. Behind you, the wall of cells over the Divide — anvils spreading east in the jet stream winds, dark bases, rain curtains. Ahead, the Front Range, the plains, Denver's skyline catching the morning sun. Clear, flat, safe.

Rachel watches the mountains recede. She's quiet for a moment. Then: "The view from up here is incredible."

"Best seat in the house."

"Too bad about Aspen."

"We'll get there. Just not this way."

You begin descending as you approach the Front Range. At 12,000 you remove the O2 cannulas. Smooth air, light winds, the suburbs of the western Denver metro visible below.

But then — a thought. From 16,500, heading east, you noticed something: the cells to the north of your outbound course, over the Gore Range, were less developed. And there was a visible corridor — wide, maybe 20 miles — between the worst of the Divide weather and the northern cells. From THIS altitude, heading east, you can see it clearly. It's the same corridor that D1 navigates.

<<link "Continue east to KBJC — you made the decision. The weather is bad. Land, drive, done." "D3a-ReturnKBJC">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continuing east to KBJC"])>><</link>>

<<link "That corridor looks flyable. Reverse course and take the northern corridor to the west side of the Divide." "D3b-TryCorridor">><<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reversing course to try the northern corridor"])>><</link>>

:: D3a-ReturnKBJC [scenario branch-d ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed at KBJC, drove to Aspen"])>>

You fly east. The descent is smooth, the approach to KBJC uneventful. Winds 280 at 10. The landing is one of those forgettable ones — smooth, centered, nothing to note. The kind of landing that follows a flight where all the decisions were made at the right time.

You park at Sheltair. It's 10:00 AM. Rental car counter is open. I-70 by 10:30. Four hours to Aspen.

The drive is beautiful. At Vail Pass, the thunderstorms are visible to the south — from the car, they look even more massive than they did from 16,500 feet. Hail pelts the windshield near Copper Mountain. Rachel watches the lightning.

"Those are where we would have been," she says.

"At 14,500, yeah."

"But we were at 16,500."

"For a little while."

"Long enough to see what we needed to see."

You arrive at 2:30 PM. Help with setup. The rehearsal dinner is at 7:00. You make it all.

<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: Strong Conservative Choice</strong>

This is a strong, conservative outcome. You climbed for situational awareness, confirmed the weather was blocking all routes, turned back without hesitation, and resisted the temptation to try the corridor you noticed on the way home. Every decision was made from a position of strength — altitude, fuel, information, and the discipline to honor a safety decision.

The climb to 16,500 cost about 10 minutes and some fuel but gave you certainty that would have been impossible from 14,500. From lower altitude, you might have pressed into the weather or agonized over the decision. From 16,500, the answer was obvious: turn around. No ambiguity. No second-guessing. The weather was serious, growing, and blocking everything.

<strong>Key Lesson: A Decision Made is a Decision Honored</strong>

The temptation to take the corridor you noticed on the way home was real. And that temptation is exactly the psychological trap that turns accidents into statistics. You'd already made the turn-back decision. You were already committed to KBJC. The corridor you noticed existed independent of that decision — it wasn't new information that changed the calculus. It was an opportunity that emerged after the decision was made. Taking it would have required reversing a safety call to pursue a risky option that you hadn't planned for.

Reversing a safety decision, even when the alternative turns out fine, is a pattern that works until it doesn't.

<strong>The Value of Conservative Decisions</strong>

The value of a conservative decision is that it eliminates the possibility of a bad outcome — even at the cost of eliminating some good outcomes. You chose not to try the corridor. That corridor might have been perfectly navigable. You might have made it through, descended to Aspen or Rifle, and arrived before the weather closed in. The probability was decent. The upside was real.

But the downside was also real. Weather can close faster than you can fly away from it. A corridor that looks navigable from 16,500 can turn into a trap the moment you commit to it. Cells can grow, winds can shift, visibility can drop. These things happen in mountain weather. The moment they happened, the corridor decision becomes catastrophic.

The decision to return to KBJC turned off that possibility. You eliminated the tail risk entirely. That's the payoff for being conservative: certainty instead of probability.

<strong>Principle: Opportunity is Not Obligation</strong>

The corridor was real. You might have made it. But noticing an opportunity is not the same as having planned for it. Your original decision to turn back was based on the full weather picture at 16,500. The reversal would have been based on a temptation — "I bet I could make it through there." That's a different kind of decision-making, and it's less reliable. One is based on systematic assessment. The other is based on optimism.

In mountain flying, systematic assessment wins more often than optimism.

<strong>The Corridor Will Be There Tomorrow</strong>

The weather corridor north of the Gore Range will exist again. Weather patterns will shift. Another day will bring a similar setup with a better window. The cost of going home is a four-hour drive. The cost of reversing a safety decision, if it goes wrong, is everything.

You chose to respect the weather. That's mountain wisdom.
</div>

<strong>Your path through this scenario:</strong>
<ul>
<<for _i, _step range $pathArray>>
<li>_step</li>
<</for>>
</ul>

