:: D3b-TryCorridor [scenario branch-d ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reversing course to attempt the northern corridor"])>>

You reverse course. "Denver Center, four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, correction — we'd like to proceed westbound again. Requesting deviation north through the corridor."

A brief pause. "Four-seven-two-golf-foxtrot, roger. Be advised, convective SIGMET three-seven Charlie is in effect from Red Table to Glenwood Springs. The corridor north of the SIGMET area is not covered but conditions are changing rapidly. Use caution."

You take the corridor. From 16,500, the gaps are visible. You thread between the cell line to the south and the scattered build-ups to the north. The ride is bumpy — moderate turbulence from the proximity of the cells — but you maintain visual contact with the terrain below and the corridor ahead. Twenty tense minutes. Rachel grips the armrest but says nothing.

You cross the Divide. The terrain drops on the western slope. The weather is behind you. The Roaring Fork Valley opens up ahead — scattered clouds, good visibility. But the weather you saw moving toward Aspen from the south is closer now. You don't have time to get to Aspen. Rifle is 20 miles to the west, in clear air.

You land at Rifle at 11:15 AM. The crosswind is manageable — 250 at 15 gusting 22. Taxi to Atlantic. Shut down.

Rachel, after landing: "That was... ambitious."

"It was a calculated risk."

"Was it worth it? We're still driving."

You think about this. You crossed the Divide. You're on the Aspen side. The drive is shorter from Rifle than from KBJC. But you flew through a corridor adjacent to a convective SIGMET, in turbulence, for thirty minutes, to save two hours of driving.

"Honestly? Probably not."

<div class="debrief">
<strong>Debrief: Safe Outcome, Weak Decision-Making</strong>

This outcome is safe, but the decision-making process reveals a critical weakness. The climb to 16,500 was excellent. The initial turn-back decision was sound. Reversing it to take the corridor was the weak link.

The corridor was real and navigable — you made it through — but you'd already decided to go home. The corridor that emerged as you were heading east wasn't new information that changed the situation. It was an opportunity that revealed itself after the decision had been made. Reversing a safety decision to pursue a risky option is a pattern of thinking that works until it catastrophically doesn't.

You got away with it this time. The weather held. The corridor didn't close. The turbulence didn't exceed your capability. You landed at Rifle without drama. But the outcome doesn't validate the decision. The decision was to reverse a safety call based on temptation. That's how accidents begin.

<strong>Key Lesson: Reversing Safety Decisions is Its Own Risk</strong>

You climbed to 16,500 to get clarity. You got it: the weather was serious, the routes were blocked, the option was to turn back. That decision was made from a position of strength and information. Then, as you were executing that decision, you noticed an opportunity that hadn't been part of the original analysis. The corridor was there, it was visible, it was tempting.

The psychological trap is assuming that because it's visible, it should be taken. Because it's achievable, it should be attempted. Because you CAN see a gap in the weather, you SHOULD try to go through it.

This is the inverse of the trap that kills most mountain pilots: pushing into weather they shouldn't. You reversed it: retreating from weather they should avoid, because a gap showed up. The direction is different; the weakness is the same. It's decision-making based on temptation instead of principle.

<strong>The Corridor North of the SIGMET</strong>

The controller's callout was precise: the corridor north of the SIGMET area was "not covered but conditions are changing rapidly." That's aviation's way of saying "this gap exists but we don't have forecast data on it, and it could close." You flew the gap anyway. You made it. But the fact that you made it doesn't mean the gap was safe to take. It means you got lucky that the gap held long enough for you to transit it.

When conditions are changing rapidly, the gap you see from 16,500 is not guaranteed to still exist at 15,000 or 14,000 or when you're committed to the corridor and can't turn around.

<strong>Principle: The Cost/Benefit Math Doesn't Work</strong>

You reversed a safety decision (return to KBJC) to take a chance on a risky corridor. The upside: two hours of driving time saved. The downside: if the corridor closed, you'd be trapped in the weather with a passenger, in a non-pressurized aircraft, in turbulence, unable to turn back. That's not a fair bet.

What changed between "I'm turning back" and "I'm trying the corridor"? Your circumstances didn't improve. The weather didn't improve. You just noticed an option. That's not a reason to reverse a decision. That's the reason most pilots regret their decisions.

<strong>What Should Have Happened</strong>

The right call at the moment you noticed the corridor was to acknowledge that it existed, note it for future reference, and continue east. The corridor will exist again. Another day will bring similar setup with potentially better margins. The cost of ignoring it this time is a four-hour drive and zero risk. The cost of taking it, if it goes wrong, is everything.

The hardest part of being a good pilot isn't skill. It's discipline. It's the discipline to honor a decision once it's made, even when an alternative opportunity reveals itself. It's the discipline to say "I see that gap, and I'm not going through it because I already made another call." That discipline is what keeps you alive.
</div>

